 Europe's internal borders to be temporarily closed,<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: European borders likely to remain open despite crisis in Italy, observers say |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3073897/coronavirus-european-borders-likely-remain-open-despite-crisis |work=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=7 March 2020}}</ref> the [[European Union]] by 13 March continued to reject the idea of suspending the [[Schengen Area|Schengen free travel area]] and introducing border controls with Italy.<ref name=\"dw-schengen\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: EU rules out Schengen border closures amid Italy outbreak |url=https://www.dw.com/en/coronavirus-eu-rules-out-schengen-border-closures-amid-italy-outbreak/a-52497811 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Salvini and Le Pen Don't Have a Coronavirus Cure |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-02-25/salvini-and-le-pen-don-t-have-a-european-coronavirus-cure |work=Bloomberg |date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Europe's open borders threatened by spread of disease |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/coronavirus-europe-open-borders-eu-italy-france-britain-germany-spain-a9362536.html |work=The Independent |date=28 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Commission chief warns against unilateral virus travel bans |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/justice-home-affairs/news/commission-chief-warns-against-unilateral-virus-travel-bans/ |work=[[EURACTIV]] |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The deputy leader of the Swiss [[Ticino League]], Lorenzo Quadri, by 29 February had criticised the decision: \"It is alarming that the dogma of wide-open borders is considered a priority.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Nightmare Could Be the End for Europe's Borderless Dream |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/world/europe/coronavirus-european-union.html |work=The New York Times |date=26 February 2020}}</ref> United States President [[Donald Trump]] said by 12 March the European Union had \"failed to take the same precautions and restrict travel from China and other hot spots\" as the US had implemented.<ref>{{cite news |title=In dramatic step, Trump restricts travel from Europe to US to fight coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-trump/trump-suspends-all-travel-from-europe-to-the-united-states-to-fight-coronavirus-idUSKBN20Z04U |agency=Reuters |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 9 March Czech Prime Minister [[Andrej Babi\u0161]] stated that \"European countries cannot ban the entry of Italian citizens within the Schengen area. The only possible way is to have the Italian prime minister call on his fellow citizens to refrain from traveling to other countries of the European Union.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Czech PM: Italians Should Be Banned From Travelling Due to Coronavirus |url=https://www.schengenvisainfo.com/news/czech-pm-italians-should-be-banned-from-travelling-due-to-coronavirus/ |work=SchengenVisaInfo.com |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland and Denmark announced complete closure of their national borders, the [[European Commission]] President [[Ursula von der Leyen]] said by 12 March that \"Certain controls may be justified, but general travel bans are not seen as being the most effective by the World Health Organization. Moreover, they have a strong social and economic impact, they disrupt people\u2019s lives and business across the borders.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Denmark, Poland and Czechs seal borders over coronavirus |url=https://www.ft.com/content/4e89ec5c-6565-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |agency=Financial Times |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> European Union leaders condemned the US decision to restrict travel from Europe to the United States. [[European Council]] President [[Charles Michel]] and Ursula von der Leyen said in a joint statement: \"The European Union disapproves of the fact that the US decision to impose a travel ban was taken unilaterally and without consultation.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=EU condemns Trump travel ban from Europe as virus spreads |url=https://apnews.com/4552fd280d06cf83c63e4cc9b08fe5ce |work=Associated Press (AP) |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> Ursula von der Leyen admitted by 17 March that \"all of us who are not experts initially underestimated the coronavirus.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Politicians 'underestimated' virus threat, von der Leyen admits |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/coronavirus/news/politicians-underestimated-virus-threat-von-der-leyen-admits/ |work=Euractiv |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Italian government has criticised EU's lack of solidarity with Italy.<ref>{{cite news |title=The EU Is Abandoning Italy in Its Hour of Need |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-eu-abandoning-italy-china-aid/ |work=Foreign Policy |date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Italy criticises EU for being slow to help over coronavirus epidemic |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/11/italy-criticises-eu-being-slow-help-coronavirus-epidemic |work=The Guardian |date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Italy wonders where Europe's solidarity is as coronavirus strains show |url=https://www.ft.com/content/d3bc25ea-652c-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |work=Financial Times |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Italy criticizes EU for not responding its call for help, 'only China responded bilaterally' |url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/2020-03-12/Italy-calls-for-extra-help-for-COVID-19-only-China-responded--ONp6w2rmvu/index.html |work=CGTN |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> ''Politico'' reported on 7 March that \"EU countries have so far refused Italy's plea for help fighting coronavirus, as national capitals worry that they may need to stockpile face masks and other medical gear to help their own citizens, officials and diplomats said.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Europe fails to help Italy in coronavirus fight |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/eu-aims-better-control-coronavirus-responses/ |work=Politico |date=7 March 2020}}</ref> Maurizio Massari, Italy's ambassador to the EU, said that \"Only China responded bilaterally. Certainly, this is not a good sign of European solidarity.\"<ref name=\"politico-corona\"/> [[Serbia]]n President [[Aleksandar Vu\u010di\u0107]] said that \"European solidarity does not exist. That was a fairy tale.\"<ref name=\"politico-corona\">{{cite news |title=China is winning the coronavirus propaganda war |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/coronavirus-china-winning-propaganda-war/ |work=Politico |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe planned [[NATO]] \u201c[[List of NATO exercises|Defender 2020]]\u201d military exercise in Germany, Poland, and the Baltic states,<ref>{{cite news |title=How coronavirus derailed the largest Nato exercise in 25 years |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/how-coronavirus-derailed-the-largest-nato-exercise-in-25-years |work=The Spectator |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> the largest NATO war manoeuvres since the end of the [[Cold War]], were to be held on a reduced scale because of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO scales down exercises due to coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-nato/nato-scales-down-exercises-due-to-coronavirus-idUSKBN21627V |agency=Reuters |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament]]'s general secretary [[Kate Hudson (activist)|Kate Hudson]] critisiced the Defender 2020 exercise: \"In the current public-health crisis, it jeopardises the lives not only of the troops from the US and the many European countries participating but the inhabitants of the countries in which they are operating.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Nato must end 'dangerous and irresponsible' military exercise on Russia's border, campaigners say |url=https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/nato-must-end-dangerous-and-irresponsible-military-exercise-on-russias-border-campaigners-say |work=Morning Star |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[PREPARE]] (EU PREPARE project)\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"OKOpress_Szumowski_EU_claims\">{{cite news | last1= Pa\u0144kowska | first1= Maria | language =pl | title= Szumowski krytykuje UE: 'Nie ma tej europejskiej solidarno\u015bci'. To wielopi\u0119trowy fa\u0142sz |trans-title = Szumowski criticise the EU: 'There is no European solidarity'. Which is false at many levels<!-- trans-title is the English translation --> | date= 2020-03-26 |newspaper= [[OKO.press]] | url= https://oko.press/szumowski-krytykuje-ue-nie-ma-tej-europejskiej-solidarnosci-to-wielopietrowy-falsz/ |quote= Bo jak by\u015bmy czekali na inne kraje, na Europ\u0119, na \u015bwiat, to by\u015bmy si\u0119 obudzili bez \u015brodk\u00f3w, a dooko\u0142a wszyscy by te \u015brodki sobie zakupili ... \u017beby by\u0142a jasno\u015b\u0107, to nie jest tak, \u017ce my ten sprz\u0119t mamy w Europie, \u017ce s\u0105 jego nieograniczone ilo\u015bci. ... Bo niestety tutaj centralne zakupy zawiod\u0142y, nie ma tej europejskiej solidarno\u015bci.  |accessdate=2020-03-26 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200326225848/https://oko.press/szumowski-krytykuje-ue-nie-ma-tej-europejskiej-solidarnosci-to-wielopietrowy-falsz/ |archivedate= 2020-03-26 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"EUCommission_rescEU\">{{cite web | title= COVID-19: Commission creates first ever rescEU stockpile of medical equipment | website= [[European Commission]] |date =2020-03-19 | url = https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/pl/ip_20_476 | accessdate = 2020-03-26 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200322164544/https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_20_476 |archivedate= 2020-03-26 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://corona.arrangy.com Worldwide Coronavirus Map, confirmed Cases] \u2013 Map the route paths of coronavirus confirmed cases.\n* [https://systems.jhu.edu/research/public-health/ncov/ ncov \u2013 CSSE] - Map of the expansion of the virus in Europe and in the world\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Europe|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in Europe]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by continent|Europe]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe| ]]\n", "name_user": "Natanieluz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePoland", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Europe"}
{"title_page": "Serenity (Clara)", "text_new": "{{short description|Sculpture by Josep Clar\u00e0}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file = Serenity statue - Washington, D.C..jpg\n| painting_alignment = Front\n| image_size = 300px\n| title = Serenity\n| alt = \n| other_language_1 = \n| other_title_1 = \n| other_language_2 = \n| other_title_2 = \n| artist = [[Josep Clar\u00e0 i Ayats]]\n| year = 1916-1925\n| type = [[Marble]]\n| height_metric = \n| width_metric = \n| length_metric = \n| height_imperial = 79\n| width_imperial = 64\n| length_imperial = \n| metric_unit = cm\n| imperial_unit = in\n| city = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]\n| museum = \n| coordinates = {{coord|38|55|19|N|77|2|10|W|region:US}}\n| owner = National Park Service\n}}\n\n'''''Serenity''''' is a public artwork by [[Catalans|Catalan]] artist [[Josep Clar\u00e0|Josep Clar\u00e0 i Ayats]], ([[1878]], [[Olot]], [[Girona]], [[Spain]] - [[1958]], [[Barcelona]], Spain) located at [[Meridian Hill Park]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]. ''Serenity'' was originally surveyed as part of the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian's]] [[Save Outdoor Sculpture!]] survey in 1993.<ref name=\"SOS\">{{cite web | author=Save Outdoor Sculptures! | year=1993 | title=Serenity (sculpture)  | work=SOS! | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!322436~!0#focus | accessdate= 18 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\nThis large sculpture is of an [[allegorical]] woman wearing long, flowing classical robes which are tied at her waist. She has long hair and stares intensely in front of her. \"Serenity\" sits on a rocky ledge with her arms casually resting on the rocks behind her. Her left foot rested on a broken sword.\n\nThe sculpture is signed on the proper left side: Jose Clara ([[Josep Clar\u00e0|Josep Clar\u00e0 i Ayats]])\n\nThe front of the base is inscribed:\n\n:SERENITY\n:IN REMEMBRANCE OF WILLIAM HENRY SCHEVTZE\n:LIEVTENANT COMMANDER VNITED STATES NAVY\n:MDCCCLIII-MCMII<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\nThe name of William Henry Schuetze is misspelled on the monument.\n\nThe statue is an outstanding example of the [[Avant-garde|avantgarde]] classical style,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gowling|first=Elizabeth|url=https://books.google.es/books?redir_esc=y&hl=ca&id=M-_pAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22josep+clar%C3%A0%22|title=On Classic Ground: Picasso, L\u00e9ger, de Chirico and the New Classicism, 1910-1930|last2=Mundy|first2=Jennifer|date=1990|publisher=Tate Gallery Publ.|isbn=978-1-85437-043-3|language=en}}</ref> which became popular in Europe and the US around [[1910]], following the work of [[French people|French]] sculptor [[Aristide Maillol]] (1861-1944). ''Serenity''<nowiki/>'s classical features and its archaic volumes are characteristics of this style, which became particularly important in [[Catalonia]], where Clar\u00e0 was born, through the [[Noucentisme|Noucentista]] movement, spanning from 1910 to [[1936]].\n\n==Background of ''Serenity''==\n\n''Serenity'' was bought by [[Charles Deering]] in [[Sitges]], a town near [[Barcelona]], [[Spain]]. Deering had a unique art collection that included many works by [[Catalonia|Catalan]] artists. In [[1916]] he commissioned sculptor [[Josep Clar\u00e0|Josep Clar\u00e0 i Ayats]] (1878-1958) to sculpt a version of ''Serenity'' for the main patio of his villa in Sitges,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mirabent|first=Isabel Coll|url=https://books.google.es/books?id=HWA6XZdGV4oC&pg=PA233&lpg=PA233&dq=serenity+clara+deering&source=bl&ots=G-5oC3AGAc&sig=ACfU3U1U8SWovvtJT3VX-eRwT5nt4gTVnQ&hl=ca&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiwgYSft7PoAhXBxYUKHfB4AcMQ6AEwC3oECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=serenity&f=false|title=Charles Deering and Ram\u00f3n Casas / Charles Deering Y Ram\u00f3n Casas: A Friendship in Art / Una Amistad en El Arte|date=2012-11-30|publisher=Northwestern University Press|isbn=978-0-8101-2843-9|language=en}}</ref> known as [http://museusdesitges.cat/en/museum/palau-de-maricel/palau-de-maricel Palau de Maricel]. However, later changes in the building forced Deering to change his mind so to locate the statue at  [[Meridian Hill Park]] as a tribute to his friend and classmate from the [[U.S. Naval Academy]] - William Henry Scheutze (1853-1902).<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\nThe sculpture was dedicated on March 12, 1924.<ref name=\"NPS\">{{cite web | author= | year=2010 | title=Points of Interest - North to South | work=Meridian Hill Park | publisher=National Park Service | url=http://www.nps.gov/mehi/historyculture/places.htm | accessdate= 17 December 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Statue Is a Curious Homage to Naval Officer, Answer Man Finds, by John Kelly, ''Washington Post Sunday'', March 22, 2009</ref> Scheutze was a naval officer from the academy who graduated in 1873 and went on to serve as a navigator on the [[U.S.S. Iowa]] during the [[Spanish\u2013American War]]. He was active in the U.S. Naval White Squadron in Chicago.<ref name=\"SOS\" /> Before his death in 1927, he became president of the [[International Harvester Company]].<ref name=\"NPS\" />\n\nThe sculpture is similar to the one located at the [[:ca:Jardins de Miramar|Miramar Gardens in Montju\u00efc]], Barcelona. The [https://museus.olot.cat/museu-garrotxa/ Museu de la Garrotxa d'Olot] holds other versions of this work.\n\n==Condition==\n\nWhen the sculpture was installed at [[Meridian Hill Park]] in 1925, the public opposed it. A petition was created opposing it's placement, citing that the subject's \"thighs were too big.\" Community members took hammers to the sculpture, creating small craters, which remain today, on the woman's face.<ref name=\"Kanter2018\">{{cite book|author=Beth Kanter|title=No Access Washington, DC: The Capital's Hidden Treasures, Haunts, and Forgotten Places|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0cd1DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA93|date=1 December 2018|publisher=Globe Pequot Press|isbn=978-1-4930-3225-9|pages=93\u201394}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960 the piece was reported as having a missing nose.<ref name=\"Clark\">Clark, Elizabeth G. \"Report of the Chronicler\" Records of the Columbia Historical Society, Washington, D.C. Vol. 60/62. p. 381.</ref> This sculpture was surveyed in 1993 for its condition and it was described as needing treatment.<ref name=\"SOS\"/> By 2009, press reports indicate it was also missing her left hand and a big toe.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> As of 2018, one of the sculpture's hands is missing.<ref name=\"Kanter2018\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Serenity Clara Proper Right.jpg|Proper right\nFile:Serenity, Meridian Hill Park, 7-13-25 LCCN2016850796.jpg|Unknown praticien sculpting details of ''Serenity''.\nFile:Miramar- Serenidad, Josep Clar\u00e0.jpg|''Serenity'' (''Serenitat /Serenidad'') by [[Josep Clar\u00e0|Josep Clar\u00e0 i Ayats]], in the [[:ca:Jardins de Miramar|Miramar Gardens of Montju\u00efc]], Barcelona. Made in 1929 for the Barcelona International Exhibition.\nFile:Ramon Casas - MNAC- Josep Clar\u00e0- 027251-D 006400.jpg|[[Ramon Casas]], ''Portrait of Josep Clar\u00e0'', 1904\u20131905. [[Museu Nacional d'Art de Catalunya]], [[Barcelona]]. \n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:1925 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Allegorical sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Artworks in the collection of the National Park Service]]\n[[Category:Marble sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:National Park Service]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Spanish art]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of women in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Statues in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sculpture by Josep Clar\u00e0}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file = Serenity statue - Washington, D.C..jpg\n| painting_alignment = Front\n| image_size = 300px\n| title = Serenity\n| alt = \n| other_language_1 = \n| other_title_1 = \n| other_language_2 = \n| other_title_2 = \n| artist = [[Josep Clar\u00e0 i Ayats]]\n| year = 1916-1925\n| type = [[Marble]]\n| height_metric = \n| width_metric = \n| length_metric = \n| height_imperial = 79\n| width_imperial = 64\n| length_imperial = \n| metric_unit = cm\n| imperial_unit = in\n| city = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]\n| museum = \n| coordinates = {{coord|38|55|19|N|77|2|10|W|region:US}}\n| owner = National Park Service\n}}\n\n'''''Serenity''''' is a public artwork by [[Catalans|Catalan]] artist [[Josep Clar\u00e0|Josep Clar\u00e0 i Ayats]], ([[1878]], [[Olot]], [[Girona]], [[Spain]] - [[1958]], [[Barcelona]], Spain) located at [[Meridian Hill Park]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]. ''Serenity'' was originally surveyed as part of the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian's]] [[Save Outdoor Sculpture!]] survey in 1993.<ref name=\"SOS\">{{cite web | author=Save Outdoor Sculptures! | year=1993 | title=Serenity (sculpture)  | work=SOS! | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!322436~!0#focus | accessdate= 18 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\nThis large sculpture is of an [[allegorical]] woman wearing long, flowing classical robes which are tied at her waist. She has long hair and stares intensely in front of her. \"Serenity\" sits on a rocky ledge with her arms casually resting on the rocks behind her. Her left foot rested on a broken sword.\n\nThe sculpture is signed on the proper left side: Jose Clara ([[Josep Clar\u00e0|Josep Clar\u00e0 i Ayats]])\n\nThe front of the base is inscribed:\n\n:SERENITY\n:IN REMEMBRANCE OF WILLIAM HENRY SCHEVTZE\n:LIEVTENANT COMMANDER VNITED STATES NAVY\n:MDCCCLIII-MCMII<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\nThe name of William Henry Schuetze is misspelled on the monument.\n\nThe statue is an outsanding example of the [[Avant-garde|avantgarde]] classical style<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gowling|first=Elizabeth|url=https://books.google.es/books?redir_esc=y&hl=ca&id=M-_pAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22josep+clar%C3%A0%22|title=On Classic Ground: Picasso, L\u00e9ger, de Chirico and the New Classicism, 1910-1930|last2=Mundy|first2=Jennifer|date=1990|publisher=Tate Gallery Publ.|isbn=978-1-85437-043-3|language=en}}</ref>, which became popular in Europe and the US around [[1910]], following the work of [[French people|French]] sculptor [[Aristide Maillol]] (1861-1944). ''Serenity''<nowiki/>'s classical features and its archaic volumes are characteristics of this style, which became particulary important in [[Catalonia]], where Clar\u00e0 was born, through the [[Noucentisme|Noucentista]] movement, spanning from 1910 to [[1936]].\n\n==Background of ''Serenity''==\n\n''Serenity'' was bought by [[Charles Deering]] in [[Sitges]], a town near [[Barcelona]], [[Spain]]. Deering had a unique art collection that included many works by [[Catalonia|Catalan]] artists. In [[1916]] he comissioned sculptor [[Josep Clar\u00e0|Josep Clar\u00e0 i Ayats]] (1878-1958) to sculpt a version of ''Serenity'' for the main patio of his villa in Sitges<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mirabent|first=Isabel Coll|url=https://books.google.es/books?id=HWA6XZdGV4oC&pg=PA233&lpg=PA233&dq=serenity+clara+deering&source=bl&ots=G-5oC3AGAc&sig=ACfU3U1U8SWovvtJT3VX-eRwT5nt4gTVnQ&hl=ca&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiwgYSft7PoAhXBxYUKHfB4AcMQ6AEwC3oECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=serenity&f=false|title=Charles Deering and Ram\u00f3n Casas / Charles Deering Y Ram\u00f3n Casas: A Friendship in Art / Una Amistad en El Arte|date=2012-11-30|publisher=Northwestern University Press|isbn=978-0-8101-2843-9|language=en}}</ref>, known as [http://museusdesitges.cat/en/museum/palau-de-maricel/palau-de-maricel Palau de Maricel]. However, later changes in the building forced Deering to change his mind so to locate the statue at  [[Meridian Hill Park]] as a tribute to his friend and classmate from the [[U.S. Naval Academy]] - William Henry Scheutze (1853-1902).<ref name=\"SOS\"/> \n\nThe sculpture was dedicated on March 12, 1924.<ref name=\"NPS\">{{cite web | author= | year=2010 | title=Points of Interest - North to South | work=Meridian Hill Park | publisher=National Park Service | url=http://www.nps.gov/mehi/historyculture/places.htm | accessdate= 17 December 2010}}</ref><ref>Statue Is a Curious Homage to Naval Officer, Answer Man Finds, by John Kelly, ''Washington Post Sunday'', March 22, 2009</ref> Scheutze was a naval officer from the academy who graduated in 1873 and went on to serve as a navigator on the [[U.S.S. Iowa]] during the [[Spanish\u2013American War]]. He was active in the U.S. Naval White Squadron in Chicago.<ref name=\"SOS\" /> Before his death in 1927, he became president of the [[International Harvester Company]].<ref name=\"NPS\" />\n\nThe sculpture is similar to the one located at the [[:ca:Jardins_de_Miramar|Miramar Gardens in Montju\u00efc]], Barcelona. The [https://museus.olot.cat/museu-garrotxa/ Museu de la Garrotxa d'Olot] holds other versions of this work.\n\n==Condition==\n\nWhen the sculpture was installed at [[Meridian Hill Park]] in 1925, the public opposed it. A petition was created opposing it's placement, citing that the subject's \"thighs were too big.\" Community members took hammers to the sculpture, creating small craters, which remain today, on the woman's face.<ref name=\"Kanter2018\">{{cite book|author=Beth Kanter|title=No Access Washington, DC: The Capital's Hidden Treasures, Haunts, and Forgotten Places|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0cd1DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA93|date=1 December 2018|publisher=Globe Pequot Press|isbn=978-1-4930-3225-9|pages=93\u201394}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960 the piece was reported as having a missing nose.<ref name=\"Clark\">Clark, Elizabeth G. \"Report of the Chronicler\" Records of the Columbia Historical Society, Washington, D.C. Vol. 60/62. p. 381.</ref> This sculpture was surveyed in 1993 for its condition and it was described as needing treatment.<ref name=\"SOS\"/> By 2009, press reports indicate it was also missing her left hand and a big toe.<ref>Statue Is a Curious Homage to Naval Officer, Answer Man Finds, by John Kelly, ''Washington Post Sunday'', March 22, 2009</ref> As of 2018, one of the sculpture's hands is missing.<ref name=\"Kanter2018\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Serenity Clara Proper Right.jpg|Proper right\nFile:Serenity, Meridian Hill Park, 7-13-25 LCCN2016850796.jpg|Unknown praticien sculpting details of ''Serenity''.\nFile:Miramar- Serenidad, Josep Clar\u00e0.jpg|''Serenity'' (''Serenitat /Serenidad'') by [[Josep Clar\u00e0|Josep Clar\u00e0 i Ayats]], in the [[:ca:Jardins_de_Miramar|Miramar Gardens of Montju\u00efc]], Barcelona. Made in 1929 for the Barcelona International Exhibition.\nFile:Ramon Casas - MNAC- Josep Clar\u00e0- 027251-D 006400.jpg|[[Ramon Casas]], ''Portrait of Josep Clar\u00e0'', 1904-1905. [[Museu Nacional d'Art de Catalunya]], [[Barcelona]]. \n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:1925 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Allegorical sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Artworks in the collection of the National Park Service]]\n[[Category:Marble sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:National Park Service]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Spanish art]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of women in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Statues in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: outsanding \u2192 outstanding, comissioned \u2192 commissioned, particulary \u2192 particularly, 1904-1905 \u2192 1904\u20131905", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serenity_(Clara)"}
{"title_page": "September 30", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\nIt is the last day of the third quarter, midway point of the second half of the year.\n\n==Events==\n* [[489]] &ndash; The Ostrogoths under Theoderic the Great [[Battle of Verona (489)|defeat]] the forces of Odoacer for the second time. \n* [[AD 737|737]] &ndash; The Turgesh [[Battle of the Baggage|drive back]] an Umayyad invasion of Khuttal, follow them south of the Oxus, and capture their baggage train.\n*[[1399]] &ndash; [[Henry IV of England|Henry IV]] is proclaimed king of England.\n*[[1520]] &ndash; [[Suleiman the Magnificent]] is proclaimed sultan of the Ottoman Empire.\n*[[1541]] &ndash; Spanish conquistador [[Hernando de Soto]] and his forces enter [[Tula people|Tula]] territory in present-day western Arkansas, encountering fierce resistance.\n*[[1551]] &ndash; [[Tainei-ji incident|A coup]] by the military establishment of Japan's \u014cuchi clan forces their lord to commit suicide, and their city is burned.\n*[[1744]] &ndash; War of the Austrian Succession: France and Spain defeat Sardinia at the [[Battle of Madonna dell'Olmo]], but soon have to withdraw from Sardinia anyway.\n*[[1791]] &ndash; The first performance of Mozart's opera ''[[The Magic Flute]]'' takes place two months before his death.\n*  1791   &ndash; France's [[National Constituent Assembly (France)|National Constituent Assembly]] is dissolved, to be replaced the next day by the [[National Legislative Assembly (France)|National Legislative Assembly]]\n*[[1882]] &ndash; Thomas Edison's first commercial hydroelectric power plant (later known as [[Vulcan Street Plant|Appleton Edison Light Company]]) begins operation.\n*[[1888]] &ndash; [[Jack the Ripper]] kills his third and fourth victims, Elizabeth Stride and Catherine Eddowes.\n*[[1906]] &ndash; The [[Royal Galician Academy]], the Galician language's biggest linguistic authority, starts working in La Coru\u00f1a, Spain.\n*[[1907]] &ndash; The [[McKinley National Memorial]], the final resting place of assassinated U.S. President William McKinley and his family, is dedicated in Canton, Ohio.\n*[[1909]] &ndash; The Cunard Line's [[RMS Mauretania (1906)|RMS ''Mauretania'']] makes a record-breaking westbound crossing of the Atlantic, that will not be bettered for 20 years.\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[World War I]]: [[Radoje Ljutovac]] becomes the first soldier in history to shoot down an enemy aircraft with ground-to-air fire.\n*[[1922]] &ndash; The [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|University of Alabama]] opens the American football season with a 110\u20130 victory over the [[Marion Military Institute]], which still stands as Alabama's record for largest margin of victory and as their only 100 point game.\n*[[1927]] &ndash; [[Babe Ruth]] becomes the first baseball player to hit 60 home runs in a season.\n*[[1931]] &ndash; Start of [[Voortrekkers (youth organisation)|\"Die Voortrekkers\"]] youth movement for Afrikaners in Bloemfontein, South Africa.\n*[[1935]] &ndash; The [[Hoover Dam]], astride the border between the U.S. states of Arizona and Nevada, is dedicated.\n*[[1938]] &ndash; Britain, France, Germany and Italy sign the [[Munich Agreement]], whereby Germany annexes the Sudetenland region of Czechoslovakia.\n*  1938   &ndash; The [[League of Nations]] unanimously outlaws \"intentional bombings of civilian populations\".\n*[[1939]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: General [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]] becomes prime minister of the Polish government-in-exile.\n*  1939   &ndash; NBC broadcasts the [[first televised American football game]].\n*[[1941]] &ndash; World War II: The [[Babi Yar]] massacre comes to an end.\n*[[1943]] &ndash; The [[United States Merchant Marine Academy]] is dedicated by President Roosevelt.\n*[[1945]] &ndash; The [[Bourne End rail crash]], in Hertfordshire, England, kills 43\n*[[1947]] &ndash; The [[1947 World Series]] is the first to be televised, to include an African-American player, to exceed $2 million in receipts, to see a pinch-hit home run, and to have six umpires on the field.\n*  1947   &ndash; [[Pakistan]] joins the United Nations.\n*[[1949]] &ndash; The [[Berlin Blockade#End of the blockade|Berlin Airlift]] ends.\n*[[1954]] &ndash; The U.S. Navy submarine {{USS|Nautilus|SSN-571|6}} is commissioned as the world's first nuclear-powered vessel.\n*[[1962]] &ndash; Mexican-American labor leader [[C\u00e9sar Ch\u00e1vez]] founds the National Farm Workers Association.\n*  1962   &ndash; [[James Meredith]] enters the University of Mississippi, defying racial segregation rules.\n*[[1965]] &ndash; The [[Lockheed L-100]], the civilian version of the C-130 Hercules, is introduced.\n*  1965   &ndash; In Indonesia, a coup by the [[30 September Movement]] is crushed, leading to [[Indonesian killings of 1965\u201366|a mass anti-communist purge]], with over 500,000 people killed.\n*[[1966]] &ndash; Bechuanaland declares its independence, and becomes the [[Botswana|Republic of Botswana]].\n*[[1967]] &ndash; The [[BBC Light Programme]], [[BBC Third Programme|Third Programme]] and [[BBC Home Service|Home Service]] are replaced with [[BBC Radio 2]], [[BBC Radio 3|3]] and [[BBC Radio 4|4]] Respectively, [[BBC Radio 1]] is also launched.\n*[[1968]] &ndash; The [[Boeing 747]] is rolled out and shown to the public for the first time.\n*[[1970]] &ndash; Jordan makes a deal with the PFLP for the release of the remaining hostages from the [[Dawson's Field hijackings]].\n*[[1972]] &ndash; [[Roberto Clemente]] records the 3,000th and final hit of his career.\n*[[1975]] &ndash; The [[AH-64 Apache]] makes its first flight. Eight years later, the first production model rolled out of the assembly line.\n*[[1977]] &ndash; Because of NASA budget cuts and dwindling power reserves, the Apollo program's [[ALSEP]] experiment packages left on the Moon are shut down.\n*[[1980]] &ndash; [[Ethernet]] specifications are published by Xerox working with Intel and Digital Equipment Corporation.\n*[[1990]] &ndash; The Dalai Lama unveils the [[Canadian Tribute to Human Rights]] in Canada's capital city of Ottawa.\n*[[1993]] &ndash; The 6.2 {{M|w}} [[1993 Latur earthquake|Latur earthquake]] shakes Maharashtra, India with a maximum [[Mercalli intensity scale|Mercalli intensity]] of VIII (''Severe'') killing 9,748 and injuring 30,000.\n*[[1994]] &ndash; [[Aldwych tube station]] (originally Strand Station) of the London Underground closes after eighty-eight years in service.\n*  1994   &ndash; [[Ongar railway station]], the furthest London Underground from central London, closes.\n*[[1999]] &ndash; The [[Tokaimura nuclear accident]] causes the deaths of two technicians in Japan's second-worst nuclear accident.\n*[[2000]] &ndash; [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict|Israeli-Palestinian conflict]]: 12-year-old [[Muhammad al-Durrah incident|Muhammad al-Durrah]] is shot and killed on the second day of the [[Second Intifada]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2003/06/who-shot-mohammed-al-dura/302735/|title=Who Shot Mohammed al-Dura?|last=Fallows|first=James|date=2003-06-01|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-10-30|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*[[2004]] &ndash; The [[AIM-54 Phoenix]], the primary missile for the F-14 Tomcat, is retired from service. Almost two years later, the Tomcat itself is retired.\n*[[2005]] &ndash; [[Jyllands-Posten Muhammad cartoons controversy|Controversial drawings of Muhammad]] are printed in a Danish newspaper.\n*[[2009]] &ndash; The 7.6 {{M|w}} [[2009 Sumatra earthquakes|Sumatra earthquake]] leaves 1,115 people dead.\n*[[2016]] &ndash; [[Hurricane Matthew]] becomes a Category 5 hurricane, making it the strongest hurricane to form in the Caribbean Sea since 2007.\n*  2016   &ndash; Two paintings with a combined value of $100 million are recovered after having been [[Van Gogh Museum#Art thefts|stolen from the Van Gogh Museum]] in 2002.\n\n==Births==\n*[[1207]] &ndash; [[Rumi]], Persian mystic and poet (d. 1273){{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n*[[1227]] &ndash; [[Pope Nicholas IV]] (d. 1292)<ref>{{cite book|author=Kristin M. Casaletto|title=Pope Nicholas IV: Franciscan Infuluence on Late Thirteenth-Century Art|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7ZZO6z_zOCcC|year=1992|publisher=Michigan State University. Department of Art}}</ref>\n*[[1530]] &ndash; [[Girolamo Mercuriale]], Italian philologist and physician (d. 1606)\n*[[1550]] &ndash; [[Michael Maestlin]], German astronomer and mathematician (d. 1631)\n*[[1622]] &ndash; [[Johann Sebastiani]], German composer (d. 1683)\n*[[1689]] &ndash; [[Jacques Aubert]], French violinist and composer (d. 1753)\n*[[1700]] &ndash; [[Stanis\u0142aw Konarski]], Polish monk, poet, and playwright (d. 1773)\n*[[1710]] &ndash; [[John Russell, 4th Duke of Bedford]], English politician, [[Lord President of the Council]] (d. 1771)\n*[[1714]] &ndash; [[\u00c9tienne Bonnot de Condillac]], French epistemologist and philosopher (d. 1780)\n*[[1732]] &ndash; [[Jacques Necker]], Swiss-French politician, [[List of Prime Ministers of France|Prime Minister of France]] (d. 1804)\n*[[1743]] &ndash; [[Christian Ehregott Weinlig]], German cantor and composer (d. 1813)\n*[[1765]] &ndash; [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Morelos]], Mexican priest and general (d. 1815)<ref>{{cite web|website=Cultura Colectivo|title=A 253 a\u00f1os de su natalicio, \u00bfqui\u00e9n fue Morelos?|author=Liss Andrade|date=September 25, 2018|accessdate=July 17, 2019|language=Spanish|trans-title=253 years after his birth, who was Morelos? |url=https://news.culturacolectiva.com/mexico/quien-fue-jose-maria-morelos-y-pavon/}}</ref>\n*[[1800]] &ndash; [[Decimus Burton]], English architect, designed the [[Pharos Lighthouse (Fleetwood)|Pharos Lighthouse]] (d. 1881)\n*[[1813]] &ndash; [[John Rae (explorer)|John Rae]], Scottish physician and explorer (d. 1893)\n*[[1814]] &ndash; [[Lucinda Hinsdale Stone]], American feminist, educator, and philanthropist (d. 1900)<ref name=\"Society1908\">{{cite book|author=Michigan State Historical Society|title=Michigan Historical Collections|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SxIzAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA336|edition=Public domain|volume=14|year=1908|publisher=Michigan State Historical Society|pages=336\u2013}}</ref>\n*[[1827]] &ndash; [[Ellis H. Roberts]], American journalist and politician, 20th [[Treasurer of the United States]] (d. 1918)\n*[[1832]] &ndash; [[Ann Jarvis]], American activist, co-founded [[Mother's Day (United States)|Mother's Day]] (d. 1905)\n*[[1836]] &ndash; [[Remigio Morales Berm\u00fadez]], Peruvian politician, 56th [[President of Peru]] (d. 1894)\n*[[1852]] &ndash; [[Charles Villiers Stanford]], Irish composer, conductor, and educator (d. 1924)\n*[[1861]] &ndash; [[William Wrigley, Jr.]], American businessman, founded [[Wrigley Company]] (d. 1932)\n*[[1863]] &ndash; [[Reinhard Scheer]], German admiral (d. 1928)\n*[[1870]] &ndash; [[Thomas W. Lamont]], American banker and philanthropist (d. 1948)\n*  1870   &ndash; [[Jean Baptiste Perrin]], French-American physicist and chemist, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1942)\n*[[1882]] &ndash; [[Hans Geiger]], German physicist and academic (d. 1945)\n*[[1883]] &ndash; [[Bernhard Rust]], German educator and politician (d. 1945)\n*  1883   &ndash; [[Nora Stanton Blatch Barney]], American civil engineer, architect, and suffragist (d. 1971)\n*[[1887]] &ndash; [[Lil Dagover]], Indonesian-German actress (d. 1980)\n*[[1893]] &ndash; [[Lansdale Ghiselin Sasscer]], American lieutenant, lawyer, and politician (d. 1964)\n*[[1895]] &ndash; [[Lewis Milestone]], Moldovan-American director, producer, and screenwriter (d. 1980)\n*[[1897]] &ndash; [[Gaspar Cassad\u00f3]], Spanish cellist and composer (d. 1966)\n*  1897   &ndash; [[Alfred Wintle]], Russian-English soldier and politician (d. 1966)\n*  1897   &ndash; [[Charlotte Wolff]], German-English physician and psychotherapist (d. 1986)\n*[[1898]] &ndash; [[Ren\u00e9e Ador\u00e9e]], French-American actress (d. 1933)\n*  1898   &ndash; [[Princess Charlotte, Duchess of Valentinois]] (d. 1977)\n*  1898   &ndash; [[Ingri and Edgar Parin d'Aulaire|Edgar Parin d'Aulaire]], German-American author and illustrator (d. 1986)\n*[[1901]] &ndash; [[Thelma Terry]], American bassist and bandleader (d. 1966)\n*[[1904]] &ndash; [[Waldo Williams]], Welsh poet and academic (d. 1971)\n*[[1905]] &ndash; [[Nevill Francis Mott]], English physicist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1996)\n*  1905   &ndash; [[Michael Powell]], English director, producer, and screenwriter (d. 1990)\n*[[1906]] &ndash; [[Mireille Hartuch]], French singer-songwriter and actress (d. 1996)\n*[[1908]] &ndash; [[David Oistrakh]], Ukrainian-Russian violinist and educator (d. 1974)\n*[[1910]] &ndash; [[Jussi Kekkonen]], Finnish captain (d. 1962)\n*[[1911]] &ndash; [[Gustave Gilbert]], American psychologist (d. 1977)\n*[[1912]] &ndash; [[Kenny Baker (American performer)|Kenny Baker]], American singer and actor (d. 1985)\n*[[1913]] &ndash; [[Bill Walsh (producer)|Bill Walsh]], American screenwriter and producer (d. 1975)\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[Lester Maddox]], American businessman and politician, 75th [[Governor of Georgia]] (d. 2003)\n*[[1917]] &ndash; [[Yuri Lyubimov]], Russian actor and director (d. 2014)\n*  1917   &ndash; [[Buddy Rich]], American drummer, bandleader, and actor (d. 1987)\n*[[1918]] &ndash; [[Lewis Nixon III|Lewis Nixon]], U.S. Army captain (d. 1995)\n*  1918   &ndash; [[Ren\u00e9 R\u00e9mond]], French historian and economist (d. 2007)\n*[[1919]] &ndash; [[Roberto Bonomi]], Argentinian race car driver (d. 1992)\n*  1919   &ndash; [[Elizabeth Gilels]], Ukrainian-Russian violinist and educator (d. 2008)\n*  1919   &ndash; [[William L. Guy]], American lieutenant and politician, 26th [[Governor of North Dakota]] (d. 2013)\n*  1919   &ndash; [[Patricia Neway]], American soprano and actress (d. 2012)\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Deborah Kerr]], Scottish-English actress (d. 2007)\n*  1921   &ndash; [[Aldo Parisot]], Brazilian-American cellist and educator (d. 2018)\n*[[1922]] &ndash; [[Lamont Johnson]], American actor, director, and producer (d. 2010)\n*  1922   &ndash; [[Hrishikesh Mukherjee]], Indian director, producer, and screenwriter (d. 2006)\n*[[1923]] &ndash; [[Donald Swann]], Welsh-English pianist and composer  (d. 1994)\n*[[1924]] &ndash; [[Truman Capote]], American novelist, playwright, and screenwriter (d. 1984)\n*[[1925]] &ndash; [[Arkady Ostashev]], Russian engineer and educator (d. 1998)\n*[[1926]] &ndash; [[Heino Kruus]], Estonian basketball player and coach (d. 2012)\n*  1926   &ndash; [[Robin Roberts (baseball)|Robin Roberts]], American baseball player, coach, and sportscaster (d. 2010)\n*[[1927]] &ndash; [[W. S. Merwin]], American poet and translator (d. 2019)\n*[[1928]] &ndash; [[Elie Wiesel]], Romanian-American author, academic, and activist, [[Nobel Peace Prize|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2016)\n*  1928   &ndash; [[Ray Willsey]], Canadian-American football player and coach (d. 2013)\n*[[1929]] &ndash; [[Carol Fenner]], American author and illustrator (d. 2002)\n*  1929   &ndash; [[Vassilis Papazachos]], Greek seismologist and academic\n*  1929   &ndash; [[Leticia Ramos-Shahani]], Filipino politician, diplomat and writer (d. 2017)\n*  1929   &ndash; [[Dorothee S\u00f6lle]], German theologian and author (d. 2003)\n*[[1931]] &ndash; [[Angie Dickinson]], American actress\n*  1931   &ndash; [[Teresa Gorman]], English educator and politician (d. 2015)\n*[[1932]] &ndash; [[Shintaro Ishihara]], Japanese author, playwright, and politician, [[Governor of Tokyo]]\n*  1932   &ndash; [[Johnny Podres]], American baseball player and coach (d. 2008)\n*[[1933]] &ndash; [[Michel Aoun]], Lebanese general and politician, [[List of Presidents of Lebanon|President of Lebanon]]\n*  1933   &ndash; [[Cissy Houston]], American singer\n*[[1934]] &ndash; [[Alan A'Court]], English footballer and manager (d. 2009)\n*  1934   &ndash; [[Udo J\u00fcrgens]], Austrian-Swiss singer-songwriter and pianist (d. 2014)\n*  1934   &ndash; [[Anna Kashfi]], Indian-American actress (d. 2015)\n*[[1935]] &ndash; [[Johnny Mathis]], American singer and actor\n*[[1936]] &ndash; [[Jim Sasser]], American lawyer and politician, 6th [[United States Ambassador to China]]\n*  1936   &ndash; [[Sevgi Soysal]], Turkish author (d. 1976)\n*[[1937]] &ndash; [[Jurek Becker]], Polish-German author (d. 1997)\n*  1937   &ndash; [[Valentyn Sylvestrov]], Ukrainian pianist and composer\n*  1937   &ndash; [[Gary Hocking]], Rhodesian motorcycle racer (d. 1962)\n*[[1938]] &ndash; [[Alan Hacker]], English clarinet player and educator (d. 2012)\n*[[1939]] &ndash; [[Len Cariou]], Canadian actor \n*  1939   &ndash; [[Anthony Green (painter)|Anthony Green]], English painter and academic\n*  1939   &ndash; [[Jean-Marie Lehn]], French chemist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate\n*[[1940]] &ndash; [[Claudia Card]], American philosopher and academic (d. 2015)\n*  1940   &ndash; [[Harry Jerome]], Canadian sprinter (d. 1982)\n*  1940   &ndash; [[Dewey Martin (musician)|Dewey Martin]], Canadian-American drummer (d. 2009)\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[Samuel F. Pickering, Jr.]], American author and educator\n*  1941   &ndash; [[Kamalesh Sharma]], Indian academic and diplomat, 5th [[Commonwealth Secretary General]]\n*  1941   &ndash; [[Reine Wisell]], Swedish race car driver\n*[[1942]] &ndash; [[Gus Dudgeon]], English record producer (d. 2002)\n*  1942   &ndash; [[Frankie Lymon]], American singer-songwriter (d. 1968)\n*[[1943]] &ndash; [[Johann Deisenhofer]], German-American biochemist and biophysicist, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate\n*  1943   &ndash; [[Marilyn McCoo]], American singer \n*  1943   &ndash; [[Philip Moore (organist)|Philip Moore]], English organist and composer\n*  1943   &ndash; [[Ian Ogilvy]], English-American actor, playwright, and author\n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[Diane Dufresne]], Canadian singer and painter\n*  1944   &ndash; [[Jimmy Johnstone]], Scottish footballer (d. 2006)\n*  1944   &ndash; [[Red Robbins]], American basketball player (d. 2009)\n*[[1945]] &ndash; [[Richard Edwin Hills]], English astronomer and academic\n*  1945   &ndash; [[Ehud Olmert]], Israeli lawyer and politician, 12th [[Prime Minister of Israel]]\n*[[1946]] &ndash; [[Fran Brill]], American actress, singer, and puppeteer\n*  1946   &ndash; [[Robert Gascoyne-Cecil, 7th Marquess of Salisbury]], English academic and politician, [[Leader of the House of Lords]]\n*  1946   &ndash; [[H\u00e9ctor Lavoe]], Puerto Rican-American singer-songwriter (d. 1993)\n*  1946   &ndash; [[Jochen Mass]], German race car driver\n*  1946   &ndash; [[Paul Sheahan]], Australian cricketer and educator\n*  1946   &ndash; [[Claude Vorilhon]], French journalist, founded [[Ra\u00eblism]]\n*[[1947]] &ndash; [[Marc Bolan]], English singer-songwriter and guitarist (d. 1977)\n*  1947   &ndash; [[Rula Lenska]], English actress \n*[[1948]] &ndash; [[Craig Kusick]], American baseball player and coach (d. 2006)\n*[[1950]] &ndash; [[Laura Esquivel]], Mexican author and screenwriter\n*  1950   &ndash; [[Victoria Tennant]], English actress and dancer\n*[[1951]] &ndash; [[John Lloyd (producer)|John Lloyd]], English screenwriter and producer\n*  1951   &ndash; [[Barry Marshall]], Australian physician and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize]] laureate\n*  1951   &ndash; [[Simon White]], English astrophysicist and academic\n*[[1952]] &ndash; [[John Lombardo]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist\n*[[1953]] &ndash; [[Matt Abts]], American drummer\n*  1953   &ndash; [[Deborah Allen]], American country music singer-songwriter, author, and actress \n*[[1954]] &ndash; [[Basia]], Polish singer-songwriter and record producer\n*  1954   &ndash; [[Scott Fields]], American guitarist and composer\n*  1954   &ndash; [[Patrice Rushen]], American singer-songwriter and producer \n*[[1955]] &ndash; [[Andy Bechtolsheim]], German engineer, co-founded [[Sun Microsystems]]\n*  1955   &ndash; [[Frankie Kennedy]], Northern Irish flute player  (d. 1994)\n*[[1956]] &ndash; [[Trevor Morgan (footballer)|Trevor Morgan]], English footballer and manager\n*[[1957]] &ndash; [[Fran Drescher]], American actress, producer, and screenwriter\n*[[1958]] &ndash; [[Marty Stuart]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist\n*[[1959]] &ndash; [[Ettore Messina]], Italian basketball player and coach\n*[[1960]] &ndash; [[Julia Adamson]], Canadian-English keyboard player, composer, and producer \n*  1960   &ndash; [[Nicola Griffith]], English-American author\n*  1960   &ndash; [[Miki Howard]], American singer-songwriter, producer, and actress \n*  1960   &ndash; [[Blanche Lincoln]], American politician\n*[[1961]] &ndash; [[Gary Coyne]], Australian rugby league player\n*  1961   &ndash; [[Eric Stoltz]], American actor, director, and producer\n*  1961   &ndash; [[Mel Stride]], English politician\n*  1961   &ndash; [[Eric van de Poele]], Belgian race car driver\n*[[1963]] &ndash; [[David Barbe]], American bass player and producer \n*[[1964]] &ndash; [[Trey Anastasio]], American singer-songwriter, guitarist, and composer\n*  1964   &ndash; [[Monica Bellucci]], Italian actress and fashion model\n*[[1965]] &ndash; [[Omid Djalili]], English comedian, actor, and producer\n*[[1966]] &ndash; [[Gary Armstrong (rugby)|Gary Armstrong]], Scottish rugby player\n*  1966   &ndash; [[Markus Burger]], German pianist, composer, and educator\n*[[1967]] &ndash; [[Emmanuelle Houdart]], Swiss-French author and illustrator\n*[[1969]] &ndash; [[Gintaras Einikis]], Lithuanian basketball player\n*  1969   &ndash; [[Chris von Erich]], American wrestler (d. 1991)\n*[[1970]] &ndash; [[Tony Hale]], American actor and producer\n*  1970   &ndash; [[Damian Mori]], Australian footballer and manager\n*[[1971]] &ndash; [[Jenna Elfman]], American actress and producer\n*[[1972]] &ndash; [[Jamal Anderson]], American football player and sportscaster\n*  1972   &ndash; [[Ari Behn]], Danish-Norwegian author and playwright (d. 2019)\n*  1972   &ndash; [[John Campbell (bassist)|John Campbell]], American bass player and songwriter \n*  1972   &ndash; [[Mayumi Kojima]], Japanese singer-songwriter\n*  1972   &ndash; [[Jos\u00e9 Lima]], Dominican-American baseball player (d. 2010)\n*[[1974]] &ndash; [[Jeremy Giambi]], American baseball player\n*  1974   &ndash; [[Tom Greatrex]], English politician\n*  1974   &ndash; [[Ben Phillips (cricketer)|Ben Phillips]], English cricketer\n*  1974   &ndash; [[Daniel Wu]], American\u2013born Hong Kong actor, director, and producer\n*[[1975]] &ndash; [[Jay Asher]], American author\n*  1975   &ndash; [[Marion Cotillard]], French-American actress and singer\n*  1975   &ndash; [[Carlos Guill\u00e9n]], Venezuelan baseball player\n*  1975   &ndash; [[Laure Pequegnot]], French skier<ref name=sr>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/pe/laure-pequegnot-1.html|title=Laure Pequegnot Bio, Stats, and Results|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref>\n*  1975   &ndash; [[Christopher Jackson (actor)|Christopher Jackson]], American actor, singer, musician, and composer\n*  1976   &ndash; [[Georgie Bingham]], British radio and television presenter  \n*[[1977]] &ndash; [[Roy Carroll]], Northern Irish goalkeeper and manager\n*  1977   &ndash; [[Nick Curran]], American singer-songwriter, guitarist, and producer (d. 2012) \n*[[1978]] &ndash; [[Ma\u0142gorzata Glinka-Mogentale]], Polish female volleyball player\n*[[1979]] &ndash; [[Cameron Bruce]], Australian footballer and coach\n*  1979   &ndash; [[Andy van der Meyde]], Dutch footballer\n*[[1980]] &ndash; [[Martina Hingis]], Czechoslovakia-born Swiss tennis player \n*  1980   &ndash; [[Milagros Sequera]], Venezuelan tennis player\n*[[1981]] &ndash; [[Cecelia Ahern]], Irish author\n*  1981   &ndash; [[Dominique Moceanu]], American gymnast\n*[[1982]] &ndash; [[Lacey Chabert]], American actress \n*  1982   &ndash; 