me Gagnon]], Canadian scholar and politician, 20th [[Lieutenant Governor of Quebec]] (b. 1888)\n*[[1973]] &ndash; [[Peter Pitseolak]], Canadian photographer and author (b. 1902)\n*[[1974]] &ndash; [[Carlos Prats]], Chilean general and politician, [[Ministry of National Defense (Chile)|Chilean Minister of Defense]] (b. 1915)\n*[[1977]] &ndash; [[Mary Ford]], American singer and guitarist (b. 1924)\n*[[1978]] &ndash; [[Edgar Bergen]], American actor and ventriloquist (b. 1903)\n*[[1985]] &ndash; [[Charles Francis Richter]], American seismologist and physicist (b. 1900)\n*  1985   &ndash; [[Simone Signoret]], French actress (b. 1921)\n*[[1986]] &ndash; [[Nicholas Kaldor]], Hungarian-British economist (b. 1908)\n*[[1987]] &ndash; [[Alfred Bester]], American author and screenwriter (b. 1913)\n*[[1988]] &ndash; [[Al Holbert]], American race car driver (b. 1946)\n*[[1989]] &ndash; [[Virgil Thomson]], American composer and critic (b. 1896)\n*[[1990]] &ndash; [[Rob Moroso]], American race car driver (b. 1968)\n*  1990   &ndash; [[Alice Parizeau]], Polish-Canadian journalist and author (b. 1930)\n*  1990   &ndash; [[Patrick White]], Australian novelist, poet, and playwright, [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1912)\n*[[1991]] &ndash; [[Toma Zdravkovi\u0107]], Serbian singer-songwriter (b. 1938)\n*[[1994]] &ndash; [[Andr\u00e9 Michel Lwoff]], French microbiologist and virologist, [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1902)\n*[[1998]] &ndash; [[Marius Goring]], English actor (b. 1912)\n*  1998   &ndash; [[Dan Quisenberry]], American baseball player and poet (b. 1953)\n*  1998   &ndash; [[Robert Lewis Taylor]], American soldier and author (b. 1912)\n*[[2002]] &ndash; [[G\u00f6ran Kropp]], Swedish race car driver and mountaineer (b. 1966)\n*  2002   &ndash; [[Hans-Peter Tschudi]], Swiss lawyer and politician, 63rd [[President of the Swiss Confederation]] (b. 1913)\n*[[2003]] &ndash; [[Yusuf Bey]], American activist, founded [[Your Black Muslim Bakery]] (b. 1935)\n*  2003   &ndash; [[Ronnie Dawson (musician)|Ronnie Dawson]], American singer-songwriter and guitarist (b. 1939)\n*  2003   &ndash; [[Robert Kardashian]], American lawyer and businessman (b. 1944)\n*[[2004]] &ndash; [[Gamini Fonseka]], Sri Lankan actor, director, and politician (b. 1936)\n*  2004   &ndash; [[Jacques Levy]], American director and songwriter (b. 1935)\n*  2004   &ndash; [[Michael Relph]], English director, producer, and screenwriter (b. 1915)\n*[[2008]] &ndash; [[J. B. Jeyaretnam]], Singaporean lawyer and politician (b. 1926)\n*[[2010]] &ndash; [[Stephen J. Cannell]], American screenwriter and producer (b. 1941)\n*[[2011]] &ndash; [[Anwar al-Awlaki]], American-Yemeni terrorist (b. 1971)\n*  2011   &ndash; [[Ralph M. Steinman]], Canadian-American immunologist and biologist, [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1943)\n*[[2012]] &ndash; [[Turhan Bey]], Austrian actor and producer (b. 1922)\n*  2012   &ndash; [[Barry Commoner]], American biologist, academic, and politician (b. 1917)\n*  2012   &ndash; [[Bobby Jaggers]], American wrestler and engineer (b. 1948)\n*  2012   &ndash; [[Clara Stanton Jones]], American librarian (b. 1913)\n*  2012   &ndash; [[Barbara Ann Scott]], Canadian-American figure skater (b. 1928)\n*  2012   &ndash; [[Boris \u0160prem]], Croatian lawyer and politician, 8th [[Speaker of the Croatian Parliament]] (b. 1956)\n*[[2013]] &ndash; [[Janet Powell]], Australian educator and politician (b. 1942)\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[Molvi Iftikhar Hussain Ansari]], Indian cleric and politician (b. 1940)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Martin Lewis Perl]], American physicist and engineer, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1927)\n*[[2015]] &ndash; [[Guido Altarelli]], Italian-Swiss physicist and academic (b. 1941)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Claude Dauphin (businessman)|Claude Dauphin]], French businessman (b. 1951)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[G\u00f6ran H\u00e4gg]], Swedish author and critic (b. 1947)\n*[[2017]] &ndash; [[Monty Hall]], American game show host (b. 1921)\n*[[2018]] &ndash; [[Kim Larsen]], Danish rock musician (b. 1945)\n*  2018   &ndash; [[Geoffrey Hayes]], British television presenter and actor (b. 1942)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/oct/01/geoffrey-hayes-rainbow-obituary|title=Geoffrey Hayes obituary|last=Hayward|first=Anthony|date=1 October 2018|work=The Guardian|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref>\n*  2018   &ndash; [[Sonia Orbuch]], Polish resistance fighter during the [[World War II|Second World War]] and [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] educator. (b. 1925)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Sonia-Orbuch-Bay-Area-woman-who-fought-Nazis-as-13285186.php|title=Sonia Orbuch, Bay Area woman who fought Nazis as a girl, dies at 93 - SFChronicle.com|date=2018-10-09|website=www.sfchronicle.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref>\n* [[2019]] &ndash; [[Victoria Braithwaite]], British research scientist who proved fish feel pain (b. 1967)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2019/oct/24/victoria-braithwaite-obituary|title=Victoria Braithwaite obituary|last=Healy|first=Susan|date=24 October 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=31 October 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n<!--Do not add people without Wikipedia articles to this list. Do not trust \"this year in history\" websites for accurate date information. Do not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence.-->\n\n==Holidays and observances==\n*[[Agricultural Reform (Nationalization) Day]] ([[S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]])\n*[[Birth of Morelos]] ([[Mexico]])\n*[[Public holidays in Poland#Holidays declared by statute|Boy's Day]] ([[Poland]])\n*Christian [[Calendar of saints|feast day]]:\n**[[Gregory the Illuminator]]\n**[[Honorius of Canterbury]]\n**[[Jerome]]\n**[[September 30 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)]]\n*[[Independence Day (Botswana)]] or [[Botswana Day]], celebrates the independence of [[Botswana]] from United Kingdom in 1966.\n*[[International Translation Day]] ([[International Federation of Translators]])\n*[[Orange Shirt Day]] ([[Canada]])<ref>{{cite web |title=What is Orange Shirt Day? |url=https://www.cbc.ca/kidscbc2/the-feed/what-is-orange-shirt-day |website=cbc.ca |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/september/30 BBC: On This Day]\n* {{NYT On this day|month=09|day=30}}\n* [https://archive.is/20121210073826/http://www1.sympatico.ca/cgi-bin/on_this_day?mth=Sep&day=30 On This Day in Canada]\n\n{{months}}\n\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:September]]\n", "name_user": "KR7907", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/September_30"}
{"title_page": "Mike Kelley (artist)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Mike Kelley\n| image =\n| caption =\n| birth_date = October 27, 1954<ref name=\"Marter\">{{Cite book |last1= |first1= |authorlink1= |last2= |first2= |authorlink2= |editor-first=Joan |editor-last=Marter |editor1-link=Joan Marter |title=The Grove Encyclopedia of American Art |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sPGdBxzaWj0C&pg=RA2-PA22 |volume=1 |year=2011 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford; New York |isbn=9780195335798 |pages=22\u201323}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Wayne, Michigan]], United States<ref name=\"Cotter\">[[Holland Cotter]], \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/02/arts/design/mike-kelley-influential-american-artist-dies-at-57.html Mike Kelley, an Artist with Attitude, Dies at 57],\" ''[[The New York Times]]'', Feb 1, 2012, accessed April 22, 2012.</ref>\n| death_date = c. {{Death date and age|mf=yes|2012|1|31|1954|10|27}}\n| death_place =[[South Pasadena, California]], U.S.\n|alma_mater=[[University of Michigan]]<ref name=\"Marter\"/>\n| field = sculpture, installation, performance\n| awards = {{ awards |award = [[Museum Ludwig|Wolfgang Hahn Prize]]<ref name=\"MKBIO\">[http://www.mikekelley.com/MKBIO.html mikekelley.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130516062432/http://www.mikekelley.com/MKBIO.html |date=May 16, 2013 }}</ref>|year = 2006}} {{awards | award =  John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation Fellowship<ref name= \"MKBIO\"/> | year = 2003 }} {{awards | award = The California Institute of the Arts Distinguished Alumnus Award<ref name= \"MKBIO\"/>| year = 2000}}\n| website = [http://www.mikekelley.com/ mikekelley.com]\n}}\n\n'''Michael \"Mike\" Kelley''' (October 27, 1954 in [[Wayne, Michigan]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{circa}}&nbsp;January 31, 2012 in [[South Pasadena, California|South Pasadena]]) was an American artist. His work involved [[found object]]s, textile banners, [[drawing]]s, [[Assemblage (art)|assemblage]], [[collage]], [[Performance art|performance]] and [[Video art|video]]. He often worked collaboratively and had produced projects with artists [[Paul McCarthy]], [[Tony Oursler]] and [[John Miller (Art History professor)|John Miller]]. Writing in ''[[The New York Times]]'', in 2012, [[Holland Cotter]] described the artist as \"one of the most influential American artists of the past quarter century and a pungent commentator on American class, popular culture and youthful rebellion.\"<ref name=\"Cotter\" />\n\n==Early life==\nKelley was born in [[Wayne, Michigan]], a suburb of [[Detroit]], to a [[working class]] Roman Catholic family in October 1954. His father was in charge of maintenance for a public school system; his mother was a cook in the executive dining room at [[Ford Motor Company]].<ref name=\"Cotter\" /> In his early years he was involved with the city's music scene, which spawned bands such as [[The Stooges|Iggy and the Stooges]], and was a member of the noise band [[Destroy All Monsters (band)|Destroy All Monsters]]. In 1976, Kelley graduated from the [[University of Michigan]] and then moved to [[Los Angeles]]. In 1978 he graduated from the [[California Institute of the Arts]] with a [[Master of Fine Arts]], where he admired the work of his teachers [[John Baldessari]], [[Laurie Anderson (performance artist)|Laurie Anderson]], [[David Askevold]] and [[Douglas Huebler]].\n\n==Work==\nDuring his time at CalArts, Kelley started to work on a series of projects in which he explored works with loose poetic themes, such as ''The Sublime'', ''Monkey Island'' and ''Plato's Cave, Rothko's Chapel, Lincoln's Profile'', using a variety of different media such as drawing, painting, sculpture, performance, video, and writing. In the 1980s he became known for working with another type of\nmaterial: crocheted blankets, fabric dolls and other rag toys found at thrift stores and yard sales. Perhaps the most famous work in this vein, ''[http://collection.whitney.org/object/7317 More Love Hours Than Can Ever Be Repaid and The Wages of Sin]'' from 1987, featured a mess of used rag dolls, animals and blankets strewn across a canvas, a way of investing a fictional childhood scene with some visceral pathos which was first shown at [[Rosamund Felsen Gallery]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324678604578340322829104276 | title=?? | work=The Wall Street Journal}} {{subscription}}</ref> In 1988, Kelley created an installation called ''Pay for Your Pleasure,'' which featured a gallery of portraits of men of genius \u2014 poets, philosophers and artists included \u2014 subverted at the end by a painting created by a convicted criminal.<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">Jori Finkel (February 2, 2012), [http://articles.latimes.com/2012/feb/02/local/la-me-mike-kelley-20120202 Mike Kelley dies at 57; L.A. contemporary artist] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref> In ''From My Institution to Yours'' (1988) and ''Proposal for the Decoration of an Island of Conference Rooms'' (1992),  Kelly appropriated photocopied drawings and other [[ephemera]] of vernacular [[office humor]] and moved it into more formalized environments where such crude materials are normally not seen.<ref>[http://www.renaissancesociety.org/site/Exhibitions/Intro.Mike-Kelley-Three-Projects-Half-a-Man-From-My-Institution-to-Yours-and-Pay-for-Your-Pleasure.110.html \"Mike Kelley, Three Projects: Half a Man, From My Institution to Yours, and Pay for Your Pleasure\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512001752/http://www.renaissancesociety.org/site/Exhibitions/Intro.Mike-Kelley-Three-Projects-Half-a-Man-From-My-Institution-to-Yours-and-Pay-for-Your-Pleasure.110.html |date=May 12, 2013 }}, [[Renaissance Society]], May 1988.</ref><ref>Doug Harvey, [http://www.laweekly.com/2003-12-11/supplement/don-t-look-back/ \"Don't Look Back: Mike Kelley's Proposal\"], ''[[LA Weekly]]'', December 11, 2003.</ref>\n\nKelley often employed soft, tangled toys as a satirical metaphor for [[Expressionist art]]. In ''Deodorized Central Mass with Satellites'' (1991\u201399), an installation sculpture made from untidy clusters of toys suspended from the ceiling, a dozen monochrome plush-toy spheres, linked by a system of cables and pulleys across the ceiling, orbit around a central, rainbow-colored blob; ten large, geometrically faceted, brightly colored wall-reliefs are actually monumental dispensers of pine-scented air freshener, which automatically send their cleansing spray into the room at timed intervals.<ref>Christopher Knight (November 8, 2012), [http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-knight-mike-kelley-rubenstein-20121105,0,1145945.story Review: A Mike Kelley sculpture makes its West Coast debut] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref>\n\nIn 1995, he produced ''Educational Complex'', an architectural model of the institutions in which he had studied, including his Catholic elementary school and the [[University of Michigan]] in Ann Arbor.<ref>[http://www.moma.org/collection/artist.php?artist_id=3045 Mike Kelley] [[MoMA]].</ref> According to the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], the work's selective inclusion of institutional locations and features responds to \"the rising infatuation of the public with issues of repressed memory syndrome and child abuse... The implication is that anything that can't be remembered is somehow the result of trauma.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mike Kelley: Educational Complex|last=Miller|first=John|publisher=Afterall Books: One Work|year=2015|isbn=978-1-84638-152-2|location=London|pages=14}}</ref> In 1999, he made a short video in which [[Superman]] recites selections from [[Sylvia Plath]]'s ''The Bell Jar''.<ref>[[Adrian Searle]] (September 7, 2011), [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2011/sep/07/mike-kelley-exploded-fortress-solitude Mike Kelley: It came from Planet Bunkum] ''[[The Guardian]]''.</ref>\n\nKelley was in the band Poetics with fellow [[California Institute of the Arts]] students John Miller and [[Tony Oursler]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}. In 1997\u201398, Kelley and Oursler presented the ''Poetics Project'' at [[Documenta]] X, as well as at venues in Los Angeles, New York, and Tokyo; through video projections, sound, and artworks, this installation re-created their experience at CalArts as members of a short-lived band.<ref name=\"Mike Kelley\">[http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/collections/collection-online/show-full/bio/?artist_name=Mike%20Kelley&page=1&f=Name&cr=1 Mike Kelley] Guggenheim Collection.</ref> Along with his collaborations with Shaw and Oursler, Kelley was also known for working with artist [[Paul McCarthy]] in the 1990s. They collaborated on a series of video projects, including a 1992 work based on [[Johanna Spyri]]'s classic children's book, \"Heidi\".<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\" /> A 1986 [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] presentation of Kelley's performance ''Plato's Cave, Rothko's Chapel, Lincoln's Profile'' (1985) included a live performance by [[Sonic Youth]];<ref name=\"Mike Kelley\" /> the band later featured his orange-knit creatures on the cover and booklet of their 1992 record ''[[Dirty (Sonic Youth album)|Dirty]]''.<ref>\"[http://www.sonicyouth.com/mustang/lp/lp9.html DIRTY]\". Sonic Youth official website. Retrieved on January 23, 2010.</ref> In 2010, he combined with [[Artangel]] to realize his first work of public art in Detroit.<ref>Michael McNay (February 2, 2012), [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2012/feb/02/mike-kelley Mike Kelley obituary] ''[[The Guardian]]''.</ref>\n\nIn November 2005, Kelley staged ''Day is Done'', filling [[Gagosian Gallery]] with funhouse-like multimedia installations,<ref>{{cite web|title=Day Is Done: Part 1|url=http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=14349|publisher=[[Electronic Arts Intermix]]|accessdate=April 11, 2012}}</ref>  including automated furniture, as well as films of dream-like ceremonies inspired by high school year book photos of pageants, sports matches and theater productions.<ref>Davis, Ben. \"[http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/reviews/davis/davis11-16-05.asp I Want My Mike Kelley]\". Artnet.com. Retrieved on January 23, 2010.</ref> In December 2005, [[Village Voice]] art critic [[Jerry Saltz]] described \"Day is Done\" as a pioneering example of \"clusterfuck aesthetics,\" the tendency towards overloaded multimedia environments in contemporary art.<ref>Saltz, Jerry. \"[http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/features/saltz/saltz12-7-05.asp CLUSTERFUCK ESTHETICS]\". Artnet.com. Retrieved on January 23, 2010.</ref> \"Day is Done\" was Kelley \"Gesamtkunstwerk\", this body of work was initiated with 'Extracurricular Activity Projective Reconstruction #1 (Domestic Scene),<ref>[https://www.vice.com/en_ca/read/mike-kelley-is-still-a-bit-like-jesus Extracurricular Activity Projective Reconstruction #1 (Domestic Scene)]</ref>\nthe work was produced by [[Emi Fontana]] and first exhibited in her gallery in Milano in 2000. In the same year Emi Fontana and Mike Kelley started a romantic relationship that lasted for seven years, and led to Fontana relocating to Los Angeles.\n\nBegun in 1999,<ref name=\"gagosian.com\">[http://www.gagosian.com/exhibitions/january-11-2011--mike-kelley Mike Kelley: Kandor 10 / Extracurricular Activity Projective Reconstruction #34Kandor 12 / Extracurricular Activity Projective Reconstruction #35, January 11 \u2013 February 17, 2011] [[Gagosian Gallery]], Los Angeles.</ref> the ''Kandor'' project (2007) deals with the town of Kandor, on the planet Krypton from which the child Kal-El escaped to Earth, where he became [[Superman]].<ref name=\"artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com\">Carol Vogel (July 12, 2012), [http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/12/watermill-center-plans-mike-kelley-show/ Watermill Center Plans Mike Kelley Show] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> Kandor's depiction in these narratives is inconsistent and fragmentary, prompting Kelley to create multiple versions of it, cast in colorful resins and illuminated like reliquaries.<ref name=\"gagosian.com\" /> The installation ''Kandor-Con 2000'' was first presented in the millennium show at [[Kunstmuseum Bonn]] and later at the [[Technical University Berlin]] (2007), the [[Deichtorhallen]]/Sammlung Falckenberg, Hamburg (2007); [[ZKM]], Karlsruhe (2008); the [[Shanghai Biennial]] (2008); and the [[Centre Pompidou]], Paris (2010). ''Kandor-Con 2000'' is conceived \u2013 and continued to develop \u2013 as a work in progress. Throughout the exhibitions, architecture students built cardboard models of Kandor inspired by the original comics. These models were sent to Pasadena, where Kelley made scaled down casts.<ref>[http://watermillcenter.org/mikekelley Mike Kelley: 1954 - 2012, A Tribute Exhibition Including Works from the Kandor Project, July 28 \u2013 September 16, 2012] Watermill Center, Water Mill, New York.</ref> ''Kandor 10A'' (2010), a yellow city housed in a hand-blown, pink glass bottle, is a grouping of tall skyscrapers situated within a full-scale rock grotto. ''Kandor 10B (Exploded Fortress of Solitude)'' (2011) is a pile of dark boulders and slabs forming a cave with a quarry-like foyer made from faux black rock and built on a scale that invites the viewer into the forbidden fortress. Set within the cave's inner recesses is a glowing rose-colored city-in-a-bottle.<ref>[http://www.gagosian.com/exhibitions/september-08-2011--mike-kelley Mike Kelley: Exploded Fortress of Solitude, September 8 \u2013 October 22, 2011] [[Gagosian Gallery]], London.</ref> ''Kandor 12'', constructed in off-white resin and evocative of a group of chess pawns, or minarets, is encased in a shadowy brown bottle, which sits on a platform resembling a Greek column positioned in front of a chest of drawers and an illuminated translucent green wall.<ref name=\"gagosian.com\" />\n\nIn 2009 Kelley collaborated with longtime friend and fellow artist Michael Smith on \"A Voyage of Growth and Discovery\", a six-channel video and sculptural installation piece.<ref name=\":0\" /> This piece was conceived in 2007 and curated by [[Emi Fontana]], produced by Kelley himself and West of Rome Public Art.<ref>A Voyage of Growth and Discovery - Vdrome</ref> The work was first installed at the Sculpture Center, New York in 2009, The Farley Building (former Kelley studio) for West of Rome in 2010,<ref>Electronic Arts Intermix : A Voyage of Growth and Discovery, Mike ... www.eai.org/title.htm?id=15073</ref> and The BALTIC Center for Contemporary Art in 2011.\n\nThe artist's last performance video was ''Vice Anglais'' from 2011.<ref name=\"artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com\" />\n\nKelley's work was inspired by diverse sources such as [[philosophy]], [[politics]], [[history]], [[underground music]], [[decorative arts]] and [[working-class]] artistic expression. His art often examined class and gender issues as well as issues of normality, criminality and perversion.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\nKelley lived and worked in various places in Los Angeles, among them the Farley Building in [[Eagle Rock, Los Angeles|Eagle Rock]].<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.westofrome.org/about-a-voyage-la \"A Voyage of Growth and Discovery\", May 26, 2010 \u2013 August 26, 2010] West of Rome, Los Angeles. Curated by creative director [[Emi Fontana]].</ref>\n\n==Death==\nIn 2012, Kelley was found dead of an apparent suicide in [[South Pasadena, California|South Pasadena]].<ref>[http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/02/01/mike-kelley-california-artist-dead-at-57/ ''The New York Times'']</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-mike-kelley-20120202,0,1424613.story?page=1|title=Mike Kelley dies at 57; L.A. contemporary artist|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=February 2, 2012}}</ref><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324678604578340322829104276 Wall Street Journal March 14, 2013]</ref> A spontaneous memorial to Kelley was built in an abandoned carport near his studio in the [[Highland Park, Los Angeles|Highland Park]] section of L.A. shortly after news of his death. Mourners were invited via an anonymous Facebook page to \"help rebuild ''MORE LOVE HOURS THAN CAN EVER BE REPAID AND THE WAGES OF SIN'' (1987), by contributing stuffed fabric toys, afghans, dried corn, wax candles\u2026building an altar of unabashed sentimentality.\" The memorial was active throughout February 2012 and was dismantled in early March 2012, with the contents given to the Mike Kelley Foundation.<ref name=\"East of Borneo\">{{cite web|last=Krasinski|first=Jennifer|title=At the End of Tipton Way: On the More Love Hours Memorial to Mike Kelley|url=http://eastofborneo.org/articles/at-the-end-of-tipton-way-on-the-more-love-hours-memorial-to-mike-kelley|publisher=East of Borneo|accessdate=2012-05-23}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\nKelley began having regular one-man exhibitions at [[Metro Pictures Gallery]] in Manhattan in 1982, and at [[Rosamund Felsen Gallery]] in Los Angeles the following year. He subsequently started to gain recognition outside Los Angeles in the mid-eighties with the sculptural objects and installations from the series ''Half-a-Man''. In 2005, he had his first solo show at [[Gagosian Gallery]] in New York City, which was representing him at his death.  A retrospective,  \"Mike Kelley: Catholic Tastes,\" appeared at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] in 1993 and traveled to Los Angeles and Munich; a second retrospective appeared at the [[Barcelona Museum of Contemporary Art|Museum of Contemporary Art]] in Barcelona in 1997; and a third was at the [[Tate Liverpool]] in 2004.<ref name=\"Cotter\" /> In 2006, his show \"Profondeurs Vertes\" was presented at the [[Mus\u00e9e du Louvre]] (2006). A major retrospective exhibition was planned after the reopening of the [[Stedelijk Museum]], Amsterdam in 2012,<ref>[http://www.stedelijk.nl/en/40051/exhibition-mike-kelley Stedelijk Museum Amsterdam: Exhibition Mike Kelley] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127115632/http://www.stedelijk.nl/en/40051/exhibition-mike-kelley |date=January 27, 2013 }}</ref><ref>[http://arttube.nl/en/Stedelijk/Mike_Kelley Video about the Mike Kelley retrospective at Stedelijk] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618034013/http://www.arttube.nl/en/Stedelijk/Mike_Kelley |date=June 18, 2013 }}</ref> and will travel to the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|MOCA]], Los Angeles in 2014. The many group exhibitions he participated in include the [[Whitney Biennial]] (1985, 1987, 1989, 1991, 1993, 1995, 2002, and 2012), [[Venice Biennale]] (1988 and 1995), [[Carnegie International]] (1991), [[Documenta]] 9 and 10 (1992 and 1997), and SITE Santa Fe Biennial (2004).<ref name=\"Mike Kelley\" />\n\nIn 2012, the [[Museum of Contemporary Art Detroit]] received a grant to complete Kelley's unfinished project ''Mobile Homestead'', a large-scale replica of the artist's home in suburban Detroit.<ref>David Ng (November 15, 2012), [http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-detroit-museum-grant-mike-kelley-20121114,0,1873526.story Detroit museum receives grant to complete Mike Kelley art project] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref> The detachable facade of the home, set on a street-legal trailer, is meant to travel from city to city hosting art, educational and social services initiatives. During its exhibition at the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles]], ''Mobile Homestead'' hosts a series of \"public service activations,\" including a lunch-making workshop led by the [[Local United Network to Combat Hunger]], a [[School on Wheels Inc.|School on Wheels]] donation drive, an [[American Red Cross]] Blood Services event and an L.A. Human Right to Housing Project/Community Action Network-hosted Rent Control Tenant Meeting.<ref>Deborah Vankin (May 30, 2014), [http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-mike-kelleys-mobile-homestead-opens20140529-story.html Mike Kelley's 'Mobile Homestead' rolls into Los Angeles] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref>\n\n[[The Watermill Center]] staged an award-winning exhibition of Kelley's video and sound installations, as well as works from the \"Kandor\" series in 2012. The Exhibition, \"Mike Kelley: 1954-2012,\" was voted \"Best show in a non-profit gallery or alternative space\" in 2012 by the [[International Association of Art Critics]].<ref name=\"Kandor\">{{cite web|url=https://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/12/watermill-center-plans-mike-kelley-show/?_r=0|title=Watermill Center Plans Mike Kelley Show|first=Carol|last=Vogel|date=|website=nytimes.com}}</ref><ref name=\"IAAC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/news-features/news/aica-announces-best-show-awards/|title=AICA Announces Best Show Awards - News - Art in America|author=|date=|website=www.artinamericamagazine.com}}</ref>\n\nOn October 13, 2013, the largest exhibition of Kelley's works opened in the [[MoMA PS1]] in New York City.<ref>[http://momaps1.org/exhibitions/view/374 MoMA PS1 presents Mike Kelley] - On view October 13, 2013 \u2013 February 2, 2014</ref><ref>The New York Times, Art & Design - [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/18/arts/design/mike-kelley-a-survey-at-moma-ps1-in-queens.html?_r=1& This Show\u2019s as Big as His Career],  By Holland Cotter, October 17, 2013</ref> The exhibition titled, \"Mike Kelley\" included over 200 of his pieces from the 1970s until his death in 2012. This was the biggest exhibition of any kind that MoMA had organized since 1976.\n\nOn December 14, 2015, a selection of Kelley's videos, from the sassy/melancholy Superman Recites Selections from 'The Bell Jar' and Other Works by Sylvia Plath (1999) to the threatening histrionics of Extracurricular Activity Projective Reconstruction #1 (Domestic Scene) (2000), as well as collaborative pieces, such as his minimalist exploration of sado-masochistic relationships in 100 Reasons (1991) \u2013 among others will be screened at [[REDCAT]] in Los Angeles.<ref>[http://www.redcat.org/event/mike-kelley-single-channel-videos]</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nDuring the artist's lifetime, German art-book publisher [[Benedikt Taschen]] and Los Angeles-based businessman Kourosh Larizadeh were the principal collectors who bought Kelley's work in depth.<ref name=\"Singular Commitment\">Susan Freudenheim (January 27, 2002), [http://articles.latimes.com/2002/jan/27/news/lv-collect27 Singular Commitment] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref> In 2001, Kelley himself donated three works by fellow artists [[William Leavitt (artist)|William Leavitt]], [[Franz West]] and [[Jim Isermann]] to the Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles.<ref>Diane Haithman (January 24, 2002), [http://articles.latimes.com/2002/jan/24/news/wk-haith24 MOCA Lists 2001 Acquisitions] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe Mike Kelley Foundation for the Arts was established by the artist in 2008 prior to his death and seeks to further Kelley's philanthropic work through grants for innovative projects that reflect his multifaceted artistic practice. The Foundation also fosters the artist's legacy more broadly and advances the understanding of his life and creative achievements.\n\n==Art market==\nIn 2007, Kelley's ''Deodorized Central Mass with Satellites'' (1991) was auctioned at [[Phillips de Pury & Company]] for $2.7 million, a price record for the artist.<ref>Kelly Crow (February 1, 2012), [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204652904577197842777238520 L.A. Artist Transformed Everyday Craft Materials Into Art] ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''.</ref> The artist's ''Memory Ware Flat #29'' (2001) sold for $3.1 million at [[Sotheby's]] in 2015.<ref>Dan Duray (November 12, 2015), [http://theartnewspaper.com/market/auctions/161000/ Records for Cy Twombly and Mike Kelley at solid Sotheby\u2019s sale] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115045717/http://theartnewspaper.com/market/auctions/161000/ |date=November 15, 2015 }} ''[[The Art Newspaper]]''.</ref>\n\n==A selection of representative works==\n*\"Mike Kelley at Skarstedt\", 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contemporaryartdaily.com/2010/05/mike-kelley-at-skarstedt/|title=Mike Kelley at Skarstedt, 2010}}</ref>\n*\"Haim Steinbach on Mike Kelley\" at Overduin and Kite, 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contemporaryartdaily.com/2008/11/haim-steinbach-on-mike-kelley-at-overduin-and-kite/#more-535|title=Haim Steinbach on Mike Kelley, 2008}}</ref>\n*\"Mike Kelley's Proposal for the Decoration of an Island of Conference Rooms (with Copy Room) for an Advertising Agency Designed by Frank Gehry\", 1992, Public Art\n*\"Heidi\", 1992, Video (in collaboration with [[Paul McCarthy]])\n*\"Pay for Your Pleasure\", 1988, Installation\n*\"Half-a-Man\", 1987\u201391, Series of objects, drawings and installations\n\n== Contributions ==\n* 2008 ''Life on Mars,'' the 2008 Carnegie International<ref>[http://blog.cmoa.org/CI08/2008/02/mike-kelley.php] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429185123/http://blog.cmoa.org/CI08/2008/02/mike-kelley.php |date=April 29, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''Mike Kelley''. (1999). Essays by Isabelle Graw, John C. Welchman and Anthony Vidler. [[Phaidon Press]]. {{ISBN|9780714838342}}.\n* Heinz-Norbert Jocks. (2001). ''Dialoge: Kunst und Literatur: Mike Kelley im Gespr\u00e4ch''. Cologne: DuMont. {{ISBN|3-7701-5096-1}}\n* ''Foul Perfection''. (2003). Essays and criticism, edited by John C. Welchman. M.I.T. Press. {{ISBN|9780262611787}}.\n* ''Interviews, Conversations, and Chit-Chat (1986-2004)''. (2005). Interviews by Mike Kelley, edited by John C. Welchman. JRP Ringer. {{ISBN|9783905701005}}.\n* Daniel Sherer. (2008). \"Heidi on the Loos. Ornament and Crime in Mike Kelley and Paul McCarthy's Heidi.\" PIN-UP 3, 59\u201362. Reprinted in Y. Safran, ed. Adolf Loos Our Contemporary (New York: Columbia GSAPP, 2012).\n* ''Educational Complex Onwards 1995-2008''. (2009). Edited by Mike Kelley and Anne Pontegnie. JRP Ringer. {{ISBN|978-3-905829-80-8}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n* {{Cite web | author = Anon | year = 2018 | url = https://exhibits.stanford.edu/women-art-revolution/feature/artist-curator-critic-interviews | title = Artist, Curator & Critic Interviews | work = !Women Art Revolution - Spotlight at Stanford | access-date = Aug 23, 2018 | language = en | archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/71t0h2ro1?url=https://exhibits.stanford.edu/women-art-revolution/feature/artist-curator-critic-interviews | archivedate = August 23, 2018 | ref = harv | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Authority control|VIAF=48863724 |LCCN=no99051579}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kelley, Mike}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Art Center College of Design people]]\n[[Category:Art in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Performance art in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Artists from California]]\n[[Category:California Institute of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Artists from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Postmodern artists]]\n[[Category:Suicides in California]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Destroy All Monsters (band) members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Mike Kelley\n| image =\n| caption =\n| birth_date = October 27, 1954<ref name=\"Marter\">{{Cite book |last1= |first1= |authorlink1= |last2= |first2= |authorlink2= |editor-first=Joan |editor-last=Marter |editor1-link=Joan Marter |title=The Grove Encyclopedia of American Art |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sPGdBxzaWj0C&pg=RA2-PA22 |volume=1 |year=2011 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford; New York |isbn=9780195335798 |pages=22\u201323}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Wayne, Michigan]], United States<ref name=\"Cotter\">[[Holland Cotter]], \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/02/arts/design/mike-kelley-influential-american-artist-dies-at-57.html Mike Kelley, an Artist with Attitude, Dies at 57],\" ''[[The New York Times]]'', Feb 1, 2012, accessed April 22, 2012.</ref>\n| death_date = c. {{Death date and age|mf=yes|2012|1|31|1954|10|27}}\n| death_place =[[South Pasadena, California]], U.S.\n|alma_mater=[[University of Michigan]]<ref name=\"Marter\"/>\n| field = sculpture, installation, performance\n| awards = {{ awards |award = [[Museum Ludwig|Wolfgang Hahn Prize]]<ref name=\"MKBIO\">[http://www.mikekelley.com/MKBIO.html mikekelley.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130516062432/http://www.mikekelley.com/MKBIO.html |date=May 16, 2013 }}</ref>|year = 2006}} {{awards | award =  John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation Fellowship<ref name= \"MKBIO\"/> | year = 2003 }} {{awards | award = The California Institute of the Arts Distinguished Alumnus Award<ref name= \"MKBIO\"/>| year = 2000}}\n| website = [http://www.mikekelley.com/ mikekelley.com]\n}}\n\n'''Michael \"Mike\" Kelley''' (October 27, 1954 in [[Wayne, Michigan]]&nbsp;\u2013 {{circa}}&nbsp;January 31, 2012 in [[South Pasadena, California|South Pasadena]]) was an American artist. His work involved [[found object]]s, textile banners, [[drawing]]s, [[Assemblage (art)|assemblage]], [[collage]], [[Performance art|performance]] and [[Video art|video]]. He often worked collaboratively and had produced projects with artists [[Paul McCarthy]], [[Tony Oursler]] and [[John Miller (Art History professor)|John Miller]]. Writing in ''[[The New York Times]]'', in 2012, [[Holland Cotter]] described the artist as \"one of the most influential American artists of the past quarter century and a pungent commentator on American class, popular culture and youthful rebellion.\"<ref name=\"Cotter\" />\n\n==Early life==\nKelley was born in [[Wayne, Michigan]], a suburb of [[Detroit]], to a [[working class]] Roman Catholic family in October 1954. His father was in charge of maintenance for a public school system; his mother was a cook in the executive dining room at [[Ford Motor Company]].<ref name=\"Cotter\" /> In his early years he was involved with the city's music scene, which spawned bands such as [[The Stooges|Iggy and the Stooges]], and was a member of the noise band [[Destroy All Monsters (band)|Destroy All Monsters]]. In 1976, Kelley graduated from the [[University of Michigan]] and then moved to [[Los Angeles]]. In 1978 he graduated from the [[California Institute of the Arts]] with a [[Master of Fine Arts]], where he admired the work of his teachers [[John Baldessari]], [[Laurie Anderson (performance artist)|Laurie Anderson]], [[David Askevold]] and [[Douglas Huebler]].\n\n==Work==\nDuring his time at CalArts, Kelley started to work on a series of projects in which he explored works with loose poetic themes, such as ''The Sublime'', ''Monkey Island'' and ''Plato's Cave, Rothko's Chapel, Lincoln's Profile'', using a variety of different media such as drawing, painting, sculpture, performance, video, and writing. In the 1980s he became known for working with another type of\nmaterial: crocheted blankets, fabric dolls and other rag toys found at thrift stores and yard sales. Perhaps the most famous work in this vein, ''[http://collection.whitney.org/object/7317 More Love Hours Than Can Ever Be Repaid and The Wages of Sin]'' from 1987, featured a mess of used rag dolls, animals and blankets strewn across a canvas, a way of investing a fictional childhood scene with some visceral pathos which was first shown at [[Rosamund Felsen Gallery]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324678604578340322829104276 | title=?? | work=The Wall Street Journal}} {{subscription}}</ref> In 1988, Kelley created an installation called ''Pay for Your Pleasure,'' which featured a gallery of portraits of men of genius \u2014 poets, philosophers and artists included \u2014 subverted at the end by a painting created by a convicted criminal.<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">Jori Finkel (February 2, 2012), [http://articles.latimes.com/2012/feb/02/local/la-me-mike-kelley-20120202 Mike Kelley dies at 57; L.A. contemporary artist] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref> In ''From My Institution to Yours'' (1988) and ''Proposal for the Decoration of an Island of Conference Rooms'' (1992),  Kelly appropriated photocopied drawings and other [[ephemera]] of vernacular [[office humor]] and moved it into more formalized environments where such crude materials are normally not seen.<ref>[http://www.renaissancesociety.org/site/Exhibitions/Intro.Mike-Kelley-Three-Projects-Half-a-Man-From-My-Institution-to-Yours-and-Pay-for-Your-Pleasure.110.html \"Mike Kelley, Three Projects: Half a Man, From My Institution to Yours, and Pay for Your Pleasure\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512001752/http://www.renaissancesociety.org/site/Exhibitions/Intro.Mike-Kelley-Three-Projects-Half-a-Man-From-My-Institution-to-Yours-and-Pay-for-Your-Pleasure.110.html |date=May 12, 2013 }}, [[Renaissance Society]], May 1988.</ref><ref>Doug Harvey, [http://www.laweekly.com/2003-12-11/supplement/don-t-look-back/ \"Don't Look Back: Mike Kelley's Proposal\"], ''[[LA Weekly]]'', December 11, 2003.</ref>\n\nKelley often employed soft, tangled toys as a satirical metaphor for [[Expressionist art]]. In ''Deodorized Central Mass with Satellites'' (1991\u201399), an installation sculpture made from untidy clusters of toys suspended from the ceiling, a dozen monochrome plush-toy spheres, linked by a system of cables and pulleys across the ceiling, orbit around a central, rainbow-colored blob; ten large, geometrically faceted, brightly colored wall-reliefs are actually monumental dispensers of pine-scented air freshener, which automatically send their cleansing spray into the room at timed intervals.<ref>Christopher Knight (November 8, 2012), [http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-knight-mike-kelley-rubenstein-20121105,0,1145945.story Review: A Mike Kelley sculpture makes its West Coast debut] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref>\n\nIn 1995, he produced ''Educational Complex'', an architectural model of the institutions in which he had studied, including his Catholic elementary school and the [[University of Michigan]] in Ann Arbor.<ref>[http://www.moma.org/collection/artist.php?artist_id=3045 Mike Kelley] [[MoMA]].</ref> According to the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], the work's selective inclusion of institutional locations and features responds to \"the rising infatuation of the public with issues of repressed memory syndrome and child abuse... The implication is that anything that can't be remembered is somehow the result of trauma.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mike Kelley: Educational Complex|last=Miller|first=John|publisher=Afterall Books: One Work|year=2015|isbn=978-1-84638-152-2|location=London|pages=14}}</ref> In 1999, he made a short video in which [[Superman]] recites selections from [[Sylvia Plath]]'s ''The Bell Jar''.<ref>[[Adrian Searle]] (September 7, 2011), [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2011/sep/07/mike-kelley-exploded-fortress-solitude Mike Kelley: It came from Planet Bunkum] ''[[The Guardian]]''.</ref>\n\nKelley was in the band Poetics with fellow [[California Institute of the Arts]] students John Miller and [[Tony Oursler]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}. In 1997\u201398, Kelley and Oursler presented the ''Poetics Project'' at [[Documenta]] X, as well as at venues in Los Angeles, New York, and Tokyo; through video projections, sound, and artworks, this installation re-created their experience at CalArts as members of a short-lived band.<ref name=\"Mike Kelley\">[http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/collections/collection-online/show-full/bio/?artist_name=Mike%20Kelley&page=1&f=Name&cr=1 Mike Kelley] Guggenheim Collection.</ref> Along with his collaborations with Shaw and Oursler, Kelley was also known for working with artist [[Paul McCarthy]] in the 1990s. They collaborated on a series of video projects, including a 1992 work based on [[Johanna Spyri]]'s classic children's book, \"Heidi\".<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\" /> A 1986 [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] presentation of Kelley's performance ''Plato's Cave, Rothko's Chapel, Lincoln's Profile'' (1985) included a live performance by [[Sonic Youth]];<ref name=\"Mike Kelley\" /> the band later featured his orange-knit creatures on the cover and booklet of their 1992 record ''[[Dirty (Sonic Youth album)|Dirty]]''.<ref>\"[http://www.sonicyouth.com/mustang/lp/lp9.html DIRTY]\". Sonic Youth official website. Retrieved on January 23, 2010.</ref> In 2010, he combined with [[Artangel]] to realize his first work of public art in Detroit.<ref>Michael McNay (February 2, 2012), [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2012/feb/02/mike-kelley Mike Kelley obituary] ''[[The Guardian]]''.</ref>\n\nIn November 2005, Kelley staged ''Day is Done'', filling [[Gagosian Gallery]] with funhouse-like multimedia installations,<ref>{{cite web|title=Day Is Done: Part 1|url=http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=14349|publisher=[[Electronic Arts Intermix]]|accessdate=April 11, 2012}}</ref>  including automated furniture, as well as films of dream-like ceremonies inspired by high school year book photos of pageants, sports matches and theater productions.<ref>Davis, Ben. \"[http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/reviews/davis/davis11-16-05.asp I Want My Mike Kelley]\". Artnet.com. Retrieved on January 23, 2010.</ref> In December 2005, [[Village Voice]] art critic [[Jerry Saltz]] described \"Day is Done\" as a pioneering example of \"clusterfuck aesthetics,\" the tendency towards overloaded multimedia environments in contemporary art.<ref>Saltz, Jerry. \"[http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/features/saltz/saltz12-7-05.asp CLUSTERFUCK ESTHETICS]\". Artnet.com. Retrieved on January 23, 2010.</ref> \"Day is Done\" was Kelley \"Gesamtkunstwerk\", this body of work was initiated with 'Extracurricular Activity Projective Reconstruction #1 (Domestic Scene),<ref>[https://www.vice.com/en_ca/read/mike-kelley-is-still-a-bit-like-jesus Extracurricular Activity Projective Reconstruction #1 (Domestic Scene)]</ref>\nthe work was produced by [[Emi Fontana]] and first exhibited in her gallery in Milano in 2000. In the same year Emi Fontana and Mike Kelley started a romantic relationship that lasted for seven years, and led to Fontana relocating to Los Angeles.\n\nBegun in 1999,<ref name=\"gagosian.com\">[http://www.gagosian.com/exhibitions/january-11-2011--mike-kelley Mike Kelley: Kandor 10 / Extracurricular Activity Projective Reconstruction #34Kandor 12 / Extracurricular Activity Projective Reconstruction #35, January 11 \u2013 February 17, 2011] [[Gagosian Gallery]], Los Angeles.</ref> the ''Kandor'' project (2007) deals with the town of Kandor, on the planet Krypton from which the child Kal-El escaped to Earth, where he became [[Superman]].<ref name=\"artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com\">Carol Vogel (July 12, 2012), [http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/12/watermill-center-plans-mike-kelley-show/ Watermill Center Plans Mike Kelley Show] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> Kandor's depiction in these narratives is inconsistent and fragmentary, prompting Kelley to create multiple versions of it, cast in colorful resins and illuminated like reliquaries.<ref name=\"gagosian.com\" /> The installation ''Kandor-Con 2000'' was first presented in the millennium show at [[Kunstmuseum Bonn]] and later at the [[Technical University Berlin]] (2007), the [[Deichtorhallen]]/Sammlung Falckenberg, Hamburg (2007); [[ZKM]], Karlsruhe (2008); the [[Shanghai Biennial]] (2008); and the [[Centre Pompidou]], Paris (2010). ''Kandor-Con 2000'' is conceived \u2013 and continued to develop \u2013 as a work in progress. Throughout the exhibitions, architecture students built cardboard models of Kandor inspired by the original comics. These models were sent to Pasadena, where Kelley made scaled down casts.<ref>[http://watermillcenter.org/mikekelley Mike Kelley: 1954 - 2012, A Tribute Exhibition Including Works from the Kandor Project, July 28 \u2013 September 16, 2012] Watermill Center, Water Mill, New York.</ref> ''Kandor 10A'' (2010), a yellow city housed in a hand-blown, pink glass bottle, is a grouping of tall skyscrapers situated within a full-scale rock grotto. ''Kandor 10B (Exploded Fortress of Solitude)'' (2011) is a pile of dark boulders and slabs forming a cave with a quarry-like foyer made from faux black rock and built on a scale that invites the viewer into the forbidden fortress. Set within the cave's inner recesses is a glowing rose-colored city-in-a-bottle.<ref>[http://www.gagosian.com/exhibitions/september-08-2011--mike-kelley Mike Kelley: Exploded Fortress of Solitude, September 8 \u2013 October 22, 2011] [[Gagosian Gallery]], London.</ref> ''Kandor 12'', constructed in off-white resin and evocative of a group of chess pawns, or minarets, is encased in a shadowy brown bottle, which sits on a platform resembling a Greek column positioned in front of a chest of drawers and an illuminated translucent green wall.<ref name=\"gagosian.com\" />\n\nIn 2009 Kelley collaborated with longtime friend and fellow artist Michael Smith on \"A Voyage of Growth and Discovery\", a six-channel video and sculptural installation piece.<ref name=\":0\" /> This piece was conceived in 2007 and curated by [[Emi Fontana]], produced by Kelley himself and West of Rome Public Art.<ref>A Voyage of Growth and Discovery - Vdrome</ref> The work was first installed at the Sculpture Center, New York in 2009, The Farley Building (former Kelley studio) for West of Rome in 2010,<ref>Electronic Arts Intermix : A Voyage of Growth and Discovery, Mike ... www.eai.org/title.htm?id=15073</ref> and The BALTIC Center for Contemporary Art in 2011.\n\nThe artist's last performance video was ''Vice Anglais'' from 2011.<ref name=\"artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com\" />\n\nKelley's work was inspired by diverse sources such as [[philosophy]], [[politics]], [[history]], [[underground music]], [[decorative arts]] and [[working-class]] artistic expression. His art often examined class and gender issues as well as issues of normality, criminality and perversion.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\nKelley lived and worked in various places in Los Angeles, among them the Farley Building in [[Eagle Rock, Los Angeles|Eagle Rock]].<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.westofrome.org/about-a-voyage-la \"A Voyage of Growth and Discovery\", May 26, 2010 \u2013 August 26, 2010] West of Rome, Los Angeles. Curated by creative director [[Emi Fontana]].</ref>\n\n==Death==\nIn 2012, Kelley was found dead of an apparent suicide in [[South Pasadena, California|South Pasadena]].<ref>[http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/02/01/mike-kelley-california-artist-dead-at-57/ ''The New York Times'']</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-mike-kelley-20120202,0,1424613.story?page=1|title=Mike Kelley dies at 57; L.A. contemporary artist|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=February 2, 2012}}</ref><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324678604578340322829104276 Wall Street Journal March 14, 2013]</ref> A spontaneous memorial to Kelley was built in an abandoned carport near his studio in the [[Highland Park, Los Angeles|Highland Park]] section of L.A. shortly after news of his death. Mourners were invited via an anonymous Facebook page to \"help rebuild ''MORE LOVE HOURS THAN CAN EVER BE REPAID AND THE WAGES OF SIN'' (1987), by contributing stuffed fabric toys, afghans, dried corn, wax candles\u2026building an altar of unabashed sentimentality.\" The memorial was active throughout February 2012 and was dismantled in early March 2012, with the contents given to the Mike Kelley Foundation.<ref name=\"East of Borneo\">{{cite web|last=Krasinski|first=Jennifer|title=At the End of Tipton Way: On the More Love Hours Memorial to Mike Kelley|url=http://eastofborneo.org/articles/at-the-end-of-tipton-way-on-the-more-love-hours-memorial-to-mike-kelley|publisher=East of Borneo|accessdate=2012-05-23}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\nKelley began having regular one-man exhibitions at [[Metro Pictures Gallery]] in Manhattan in 1982, and at [[Rosamund Felsen Gallery]] in Los Angeles the following year. He subsequently started to gain recognition outside Los Angeles in the mid-eighties with the sculptural objects and installations from the series ''Half-a-Man''. In 2005, he had his first solo show at [[Gagosian Gallery]] in New York City, which was representing him at his death.  A retrospective,  \"Mike Kelley: Catholic Tastes,\" appeared at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] in 1993 and traveled to Los Angeles and Munich; a second retrospective appeared at the [[Barcelona Museum of Contemporary Art|Museum of Contemporary Art]] in Barcelona in 1997; and a third was at the [[Tate Liverpool]] in 2004.<ref name=\"Cotter\" /> In 2006, his show \"Profondeurs Vertes\" was presented at the [[Mus\u00e9e du Louvre]] (2006). A major retrospective exhibition was planned after the reopening of the [[Stedelijk Museum]], Amsterdam in 2012,<ref>[http://www.stedelijk.nl/en/40051/exhibition-mike-kelley Stedelijk Museum Amsterdam: Exhibition Mike Kelley] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127115632/http://www.stedelijk.nl/en/40051/exhibition-mike-kelley |date=January 27, 2013 }}</ref><ref>[http://arttube.nl/en/Stedelijk/Mike_Kelley Video about the Mike Kelley retrospective at Stedelijk] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618034013/http://www.arttube.nl/en/Stedelijk/Mike_Kelley |date=June 18, 2013 }}</ref> and will travel to the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|MOCA]], Los Angeles in 2014. The many group exhibitions he participated in include the [[Whitney Biennial]] (1985, 1987, 1989, 1991, 1993, 1995, 2002, and 2012), [[Venice Biennale]] (1988 and 1995), [[Carnegie International]] (1991), [[Documenta]] 9 and 10 (1992 and 1997), and SITE Santa Fe Biennial (2004).<ref name=\"Mike Kelley\" />\n\nIn 2012, the [[Museum of Contemporary Art Detroit]] received a grant to complete Kelley's unfinished project ''Mobile Homestead'', a large-scale replica of the artist's home in suburban Detroit.<ref>David Ng (November 15, 2012), [http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-detroit-museum-grant-mike-kelley-20121114,0,1873526.story Detroit museum receives grant to complete Mike Kelley art project] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref> The detachable facade of the home, set on a street-legal trailer, is meant to travel from city to city hosting art, educational and social services initiatives. During its exhibition at the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles]], ''Mobile Homestead'' hosts a series of \"public service activations,\" including a lunch-making workshop led by the [[Local United Network to Combat Hunger]], a [[School on Wheels Inc.|School on Wheels]] donation drive, an [[American Red Cross]] Blood Services event and an L.A. Human Right to Housing Project/Community Action Network-hosted Rent Control Tenant Meeting.<ref>Deborah Vankin (May 30, 2014), [http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-mike-kelleys-mobile-homestead-opens20140529-story.html Mike Kelley's 'Mobile Homestead' rolls into Los Angeles] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref>\n\n[[The Watermill Center]] staged an award-winning exhibition of Kelley's video and sound installations, as well as works from the \"Kandor\" series in 2012. The Exhibition, \"Mike Kelley: 1954-2012,\" was voted \"Best show in a non-profit gallery or alternative space\" in 2012 by the [[International Association of Art Critics]].<ref name=\"Kandor\">{{cite web|url=https://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/12/watermill-center-plans-mike-kelley-show/?_r=0|title=Watermill Center Plans Mike Kelley Show|first=Carol|last=Vogel|date=|website=nytimes.com}}</ref><ref name=\"IAAC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/news-features/news/aica-announces-best-show-awards/|title=AICA Announces Best Show Awards - News - Art in America|author=|date=|website=www.artinamericamagazine.com}}</ref>\n\nOn October 13, 2013, the largest exhibition of Kelley's works opened in the [[MoMA PS1]] in New York City.<ref>[http://momaps1.org/exhibitions/view/374 MoMA PS1 presents Mike Kelley] - On view October 13, 2013 \u2013 February 2, 2014</ref><ref>The New York Times, Art & Design - [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/18/arts/design/mike-kelley-a-survey-at-moma-ps1-in-queens.html?_r=1& This Show\u2019s as Big as His Career],  By Holland Cotter, October 17, 2013</ref> The exhibition titled, \"Mike Kelley\" included over 200 of his pieces from the 1970s until his death in 2012. This was the biggest exhibition of any kind that MoMA had organized since 1976.\n\nOn December 14, 2015, a selection of Kelley's videos, from the sassy/melancholy Superman Recites Selections from 'The Bell Jar' and Other Works by Sylvia Plath (1999) to the threatening histrionics of Extracurricular Activity Projective Reconstruction #1 (Domestic Scene) (2000), as well as collaborative pieces, such as his minimalist exploration of sado-masochistic relationships in 100 Reasons (1991) \u2013 among others will be screened at [[REDCAT]] in Los Angeles.<ref>[http://www.redcat.org/event/mike-kelley-single-channel-videos]</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nDuring the artist's lifetime, German art-book publisher [[Benedikt Taschen]] and Los Angeles-based businessman Kourosh Larizadeh were the principal collectors who bought Kelley's work in depth.<ref name=\"Singular Commitment\">Susan Freudenheim (January 27, 2002), [http://articles.latimes.com/2002/jan/27/news/lv-collect27 Singular Commitment] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref> In 2001, Kelley himself donated three works by fellow artists [[William Leavitt (artist)|William Leavitt]], [[Franz West]] and [[Jim Isermann]] to the Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles.<ref>Diane Haithman (January 24, 2002), [http://articles.latimes.com/2002/jan/24/news/wk-haith24 MOCA Lists 2001 Acquisitions] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe Mike Kelley Foundation for the Arts was established by the artist in 2008 prior to his death and seeks to further Kelley's philanthropic work through grants for innovative projects that reflect his multifaceted artistic practice. The Foundation also fosters the artist's legacy more broadly and advances the understanding of his life and creative achievements.\n\n==Art market==\nIn 2007, Kelley's ''Deodorized Central Mass with Satellites'' (1991) was auctioned at [[Phillips de Pury & Company]] for $2.7 million, a price record for the artist.<ref>Kelly Crow (February 1, 2012), [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204652904577197842777238520 L.A. Artist Transformed Everyday Craft Materials Into Art] ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''.</ref> The artist's ''Memory Ware Flat #29'' (2001) sold for $3.1 million at [[Sotheby's]] in 2015.<ref>Dan Duray (November 12, 2015), [http://theartnewspaper.com/market/auctions/161000/ Records for Cy Twombly and Mike Kelley at solid Sotheby\u2019s sale] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115045717/http://theartnewspaper.com/market/auctions/161000/ |date=November 15, 2015 }} ''[[The Art Newspaper]]''.</ref>\n\n==A selection of representative works==\n*\"Mike Kelley at Skarstedt\", 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contemporaryartdaily.com/2010/05/mike-kelley-at-skarstedt/|title=Mike Kelley at Skarstedt, 2010}}</ref>\n*\"Haim Steinbach on Mike Kelley\" at Overduin and Kite, 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contemporaryartdaily.com/2008/11/haim-steinbach-on-mike-kelley-at-overduin-and-kite/#more-535|title=Haim Steinbach on Mike Kelley, 2008}}</ref>\n*\"Mike Kelley's Proposal for the Decoration of an Island of Conference Rooms (with Copy Room) for an Advertising Agency Designed by Frank Gehry\", 1992, Public Art\n*\"Heidi\", 1992, Video (in collaboration with [[Paul McCarthy]])\n*\"Pay for Your Pleasure\", 1988, Installation\n*\"Half-a-Man\", 1987\u201391, Series of objects, drawings and installations\n\n== Contributions ==\n* 2008 ''Life on Mars,'' the 2008 Carnegie International<ref>[http://blog.cmoa.org/CI08/2008/02/mike-kelley.php] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429185123/http://blog.cmoa.org/CI08/2008/02/mike-kelley.php |date=April 29, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''Mike Kelley''. (1999). Essays by Isabelle Graw, John C. Welchman and Anthony Vidler. [[Phaidon Press]]. {{ISBN|9780714838342}}.\n* Heinz-Norbert Jocks. (2001). ''Dialoge: Kunst und Literatur: Mike Kelley im Gespr\u00e4ch''. Cologne: DuMont. {{ISBN|3-7701-5096-1}}\n* ''Foul Perfection''. (2003). Essays and criticism, edited by John C. Welchman. M.I.T. Press. {{ISBN|9780262611787}}.\n* ''Interviews, Conversations, and Chit-Chat (1986-2004)''. (2005). Interviews by Mike Kelley, edited by John C. Welchman. JRP Ringer. {{ISBN|9783905701005}}.\n* Daniel Sherer. (2008). \"Heidi on the Loos. Ornament and Crime in Mike Kelley and Paul McCarthy's Heidi.\" PIN-UP 3, 59\u201362. Reprinted in Y. Safran, ed. Adolf Loos Our Contemporary (New York: Columbia GSAPP, 2012).\n* ''Educational Complex Onwards 1995-2008''. (2009). Edited by Mike Kelley and Anne Pontegnie. JRP Ringer. {{ISBN|978-3-905829-80-8}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n* {{Cite web | author = Anon | year = 2018 | url = https://exhibits.stanford.edu/women-art-revolution/feature/artist-curator-critic-interviews | title = Artist, Curator & Critic Interviews | work = !Women Art Revolution - Spotlight at Stanford | access-date = Aug 23, 2018 | language = en | archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/71t0h2ro1?url=https://exhibits.stanford.edu/women-art-revolution/feature/artist-curator-critic-interviews | archivedate = August 23, 2018 | ref = harv | url-status=live | df = mdy-all }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{external links|date=February 2012}}\n* [http://www.mikekelleyfoundation.org/ Official site]\n* [http://www.elienation.org/mike-kelley-interview.html \"105 Minutes with Mike\" 2004 Video Interview] by Gerry Fialka and Eli Elliott. \n* [https://www.pbs.org/art21/artists/kelley/ Biography, interviews, essays, artwork images and video clips] from [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] series ''[[Art:21 -- Art in the Twenty-First Century]]''  - Season 1 (2001).\n* [http://www.gagosian.com/artists/mike-kelley/ Mike Kelley] at Gagosian Gallery\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071201051738/http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/tomorrow_never_comes1/ \"Tomorrow Never Comes\"] Steven Stern on Kelley, ''Frieze'', March, 2006\n*Daniel Sherer, \"Heidi on the Loos. Ornament and Crime in Mike Kelley and Paul McCarthy\u2019s Heidi.\" PIN-UP 3 (2008), 59\u201362.\n* Mike Kelley is a member of [https://web.archive.org/web/20060715042605/http://x-traonline.org/aboutXTRA.htm Project X Foundation for Art and Criticism], publisher of [http://www.x-traonline.org X-TRA]\n* [http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/reviews/davis/davis11-16-05.asp \"I Want My Mike Kelley\"] by Ben Davis, Artnet Magazine\n* [http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/features/saltz/saltz12-7-05.asp \"Clusterfuck Aesthetics\"] by Jerry Saltz, Artnet Magazine\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070812104042/http://wha.ucdavis.edu/PREVIOUS/1999/mike_kelley.htm Mike Kelley and the Conceptual Vernacular]\n* Exhibitions and works at [http://www.jablonkagalerie.com Jablonka Galerie]\n* Exhihibition and work at [http://www.perryrubenstein.com Perry Rubenstein Gallery]\n* Kelly Crow (March 14, 2013), [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324678604578340322829104276 The Escape Artist] ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131003044728/http://kadist.org/en/people/mike-kelley Mike Kelley] at [[Kadist Art Foundation]]\n* [http://www.kapsul.org/public/mike-kelley Mike Kelley Kapsul Image Collection]\n\n{{Authority control|VIAF=48863724 |LCCN=no99051579}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kelley, Mike}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Art Center College of Design people]]\n[[Category:Art in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Performance art in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Artists from California]]\n[[Category:California Institute of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Artists from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Postmodern artists]]\n[[Category:Suicides in California]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Destroy All Monsters (band) members]]\n", "name_user": "QueerEcofeminist", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Kelley_(artist)"}
{"title_page": "Chinese water torture", "text_new": "{{For|the device used by [[Illusionist|illusionists]], most notably [[Harry Houdini]]|Chinese Water Torture Cell}}{{More citations needed|date=June 2018}}[[File:SingSing torture 1860.png|thumb|A victim of Chinese water torture at [[Sing Sing Prison]] in [[Ossining (town), New York|Ossining, New York]], circa 1860 ]]\n[[Image:Chinesische Wasserfolter - Gedenkst\u00e4tte Berlin-Hohensch\u00f6nhausen.jpg|thumb|A rep of a Chinese water torture apparatus at [[Berlin-Hohensch\u00f6nhausen Memorial]]]]\n'''Chinese water torture''' is a painful process in which cold water is slowly dripped onto the scalp, forehead or face for a prolonged period of time allegedly making the restrained victim [[insanity|insane]]. This form of torture was first term by [[Hippolytus de Marsiliis|Hippolytus De Marsiliis]] in [[Italy]] in the 15th or 16th century.  <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Wrong View of History|last=Paraskovich|first=Jack|publisher=|year=2016|isbn=978-1-4771-2395-9|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Origin==\nThe term \"Chinese water torture\" may have arisen from [[Chinese Water Torture Cell]] (a feat of [[escapology]] introduced in Berlin at Circus Busch on September 13, 1910). The escape entailed [[Harry Houdini]] being bound and suspended upside-down in a locked glass and steel cabinet full to overflowing with water, from which he escaped, together with the [[Fu Manchu]] stories of [[Sax Rohmer]] that were popular in the 1930's (in which [[Fu Manchu]] subjected his victims to various ingenious tortures, such as the wired jacket). [[Hippolytus de Marsiliis]] is credited with the invention of a form of water torture. Having observed how drops of water falling one by one on a stone gradually created a hollow, he applied the method to the human body. Other suggestions say that the term \"Chinese water torture\" was invented merely to grant the method a sense of ominous mystery. The victim would be stripped of their clothes, shown to the public, then tortured. They would be driven insane while bystanders watched, mocked, and laughed at them.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Effectiveness==\nThere is very little evidence pertaining to the effectiveness of the method. The television series ''[[MythBusters]]'' investigated the effectiveness of Chinese water torture, and while it was found quite effective, they noted that the restraining equipment was providing most of the effect by itself, and when testing the dripping water alone on a relaxed, unrestrained subject, it was found almost negligible.<ref>[[MythBusters|Mythbusters]], \"Water Torture\". Episode 25, Season 2. (2005)</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Corporal punishment|Corporal Punishment]]\n*[[Insanity]]\n*[Water cure (torture)|Water cure]\n* [[Water torture]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Physical torture techniques]]\n[[Category:Psychological torture techniques]]\n[[Category:Water torture]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the device used by [[Illusionist|illusionists]], most notably [[Harry Houdini]]|Chinese Water Torture Cell}}{{More citations needed|date=June 2018}}[[File:SingSing torture 1860.png|thumb|A victim of Chinese water torture at [[Sing Sing Prison]] in [[Ossining (town), New York|Ossining, New York]], circa 1860 ]]\n[[Image:Chinesische Wasserfolter - Gedenkst\u00e4tte Berlin-Hohensch\u00f6nhausen.jpg|thumb|A reproduction of a Chinese water torture apparatus at [[Berlin-Hohensch\u00f6nhausen Memorial]]]]\n'''Chinese water torture''' is a painful process in which cold water is slowly dripped onto the scalp, forehead or face for a prolonged period of time allegedly making the restrained victim [[insanity|insane]]. This form of torture was first term by [[Hippolytus de Marsiliis|Hippolytus De Marsiliis]] in [[Italy]] in the 15th or 16th century.  <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Wrong View of History|last=Paraskovich|first=Jack|publisher=|year=2016|isbn=978-1-4771-2395-9|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Origin==\nThe term \"Chinese water torture\" may have arisen from [[Chinese Water Torture Cell]] (a feat of [[escapology]] introduced in Berlin at Circus Busch on September 13, 1910). The escape entailed [[Harry Houdini]] being bound and suspended upside-down in a locked glass and steel cabinet full to overflowing with water, from which he escaped, together with the [[Fu Manchu]] stories of [[Sax Rohmer]] that were popular in the 1930's (in which [[Fu Manchu]] subjected his victims to various ingenious tortures, such as the wired jacket). [[Hippolytus de Marsiliis]] is credited with the invention of a form of water torture. Having observed how drops of water falling one by one on a stone gradually created a hollow, he applied the method to the human body. Other suggestions say that the term \"Chinese water torture\" was invented merely to grant the method a sense of ominous mystery. The victim would be stripped of their clothes, shown to the public, then tortured. They would be driven insane while bystanders watched, mocked, and laughed at them.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Effectiveness==\nThere is very little evidence pertaining to the effectiveness of the method. The television series ''[[MythBusters]]'' investigated the effectiveness of Chinese water torture, and while it was found quite effective, they noted that the restraining equipment was providing most of the effect by itself, and when testing the dripping water alone on a relaxed, unrestrained subject, it was found almost negligible.<ref>[[MythBusters|Mythbusters]], \"Water Torture\". Episode 25, Season 2. (2005)</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Corporal punishment|Corporal Punishment]]\n*[[Insanity]]\n*[[Water cure (torture)|Water cure]]\n* [[Water torture]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Physical torture techniques]]\n[[Category:Psychological torture techniques]]\n[[Category:Water torture]]\n", "name_user": "69.117.6.188", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_water_torture"}
{"title_page": "Jun Hong Lu", "text_new": "{{short description|Chinese-Australian religious leader}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=April 2017}}\n{{COI|date=July 2016}}\n{{Third-party|date=September 2019}}\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Lu (surname \u5362)|Lu]]}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jun Hong Lu\n| native_name        = \u5362\u519b\u5b8f\n| native_name_lang   = zh\n| image              = Lu Jun Hong.jpg\n| caption            = Lu Jun Hong's photo on a advertisement flyer\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=y|1959|08|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shanghai, China]]\n| nationality        = Australian\n| occupation         = {{ubl| Chairman of Australia Oriental Media Group | President of Australian Chinese Buddhist Research Center }}\n| known_for          = Founder of the Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door\n| website            = {{url|richardjunhonglu.org}}\n| module             = {{Infobox Chinese |child =yes\n| title   = Lu Junhong\n| t       = {{linktext|\u76e7|\u8ecd|\u5b8f}}\n| s       = {{linktext|\u5362|\u519b|\u5b8f}}\n| p       = L\u00fa J\u016bnh\u00f3ng\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Jun Hong Lu''' ({{zh|t=\u76e7\u8ecd\u5b8f|p=L\u00fa J\u016bnh\u00f3ng}}, born 4 August 1959) is the leader of the organization \"Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door\" along with several other religions organizations owned by himself. The Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door created by Lu has been denounced by Malaysian Buddhist Community and Singapore Buddhist Federation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chinabuddhismencyclopedia.com/en/index.php/Malaysia_Buddhist_Community_Warns_About_Lu_Jun_Hong |title=Malaysia Buddhist Community Warns About Lu Jun Hong - Chinese Buddhist Encyclopedia |website=www.chinabuddhismencyclopedia.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://en.itisalllie.com/ |title=World Zhengxin Buddhist Association |website=en.itisalllie.com |access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nLu was born on 4 August 1959, at [[Shanghai, China]]. He later migrated to Australia in the late 80s and became an Australian citizen.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://guanyincitta.com/en/master-lu-biography/ |title=Biography of Master Jun Hong Lu - Guan Yin Citta}}</ref> In 2010, he launched the Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door organization and created the Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door religious belief.\n\n== Awards ==\nOn 31 March 2014, Lu was awarded an honorary visiting professorship by the [[University of Siena]], Italy through their Master Program in Global Governance and Cultural Diplomacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guanyincitta.com/en/master-lu-awarded-honorary-visiting-professorship-by-university-of-siena-in-italy/ |title=Master Lu Awarded Honorary Visiting Professorship by University of Siena in Italy |publisher=Guan Yin Citta |accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nJun Hong Lu is featured in the 2014 edition of the \u201cYearbook of Who's Who of China 2014\".<ref>''\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u7269\u5e74\u9274 2014''. ''\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u7269\u5e74\u9274\u793e'', 2014. p451.</ref>\n\n== Religious activities ==\n[[File:Sportshub-Singapore-Jun-Hong-Lu.jpg|upright|thumb|The Grand Dharma Talk by Jun Hong Lu in National Stadium Singapore 2017]]\n[[File:Jun Hong Lu giving a conference at Paris-Bercy - 2019-09-08.jpg|thumb|Jun Hong Lu giving a conference at [[AccorHotels Arena]] at Paris in 2019 ]]\nLu create an organization in 2010 and publicizes his own religious belief called Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door (Chinese: \u89c0\u4e16\u97f3\u83e9\u85a9\u5fc3\u9748\u6cd5\u9580). Since 2010, Lu and his Propagating Team respond to Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door follower's invitations by organizing public talks in many countries and regions including major cities in Australia; New York, Los Angeles, San Francisco and Boston in the United States; and Toronto and Vancouver in Canada, Brussels in Belgium and Madrid in Spain and Rome in Italy. Lu also gave talks in Singapore, Malaysia, Hong Kong, UK, France, Germany, Denmark, Thailand, New Zealand, and Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guanyincitta.com/en/events/|title=Events|publisher=Guan Yin Citta|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> The Dharma Convention held by Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door allows visitors to enter for free. And also, the discipleship initiation ceremony is conducted for free.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/dharma-facts/|title=Guan Yin Citta Convention - Free Entrance|last=Facts|first=Dharma}}</ref> In December 2013 Lu was invited to give a speech at Institute for Cultural Diplomacy (ICD)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cd-n.org/|title=CD-N.ORG &#124;}}</ref> in recognition of Jun Hong Lu's contribution to the international community.\n\n==Publications==\nLu has written more than 30 books related to Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door, and giving away his books for free,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gyph.org/xinlingfamenshuji/|title=\u5362\u53f0\u957f \u89c2\u4e16\u97f3\u83e9\u8428 \u5fc3\u7075\u6cd5\u95e8 \u4e66\u7c4d - \u5362\u53f0\u957f\u8457}}</ref> and some of his books were being translated into English, French, Spanish and German.<ref>[http://richardjunhonglu.org/jun-hong-lu-publications/ Publications - Master Jun Hong Lu | Official Website<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Although it claims that the books are giving away for free, Lu also sell his books to his believers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.itisalllie.com/|title=World Zhengxin Buddhist Association|website=en.itisalllie.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\n=== Buddhism and Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door ===\nAccording to Jun Hong Lu, Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door belongs to the [[Mahayana]] Buddhist tradition, and he encourages people to recite Buddhist scriptures (sutras and mantras) on a daily basis, practice life liberation (that is, saving the lives of beings destined for slaughter), and make great vows to help more people. He created the three \"golden practices\" and also claim that it will lay a solid foundation for improved physical and mental well-being.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |date= |title=Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door |url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B_Rz2U4PrI50VU1xUi1JZkxSVEE/view |location= |publisher= |page=4 |isbn=}}</ref>\n\n====3 steps of Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door's practice====\n#Reciting Buddhist sutras/mantras: Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door believes that reciting Buddhist sutras and mantras on a daily basis helps one benefit from the blessings of Buddhas and Bodhisattvas. Recitation will not only help eliminate one's negative karma; it will also bring strength, wisdom and inner peace, so that one can overcome all kinds of obstacles. The three major sutras and mantras recited by Guan Yin Citta followers are: [[N\u012blaka\u1e47\u1e6dha Dh\u0101ra\u1e47\u012b|the Great Compassion Mantra]], the [[Heart Sutra]], and the Eighty-eight Buddhas Repentance.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |date= |title=Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door |url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B_Rz2U4PrI50VU1xUi1JZkxSVEE/view |location= |publisher= |page=7 |isbn=}}</ref>\n#Practicing life liberation: that is, Release of animals, especially those in grave danger of being killed, is a popular practice performed by all schools of [[Buddhism]]. Guan Yin Citta believes that setting animals free helps one cultivate compassion towards all beings, and deepens the understanding that all living beings are all interdependent.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://lujunhong2or.com/%E7%B2%BE%E5%BD%A9%E5%BC%80%E7%A4%BA%E4%B8%93%E9%A2%98%EF%BC%9A%E6%95%91%E5%BD%BC%E5%91%BD%EF%BC%8C%E6%95%91%E5%B7%B1%E5%BF%83%EF%BC%88%E4%B8%8A%EF%BC%89-%E6%94%BE%E7%94%9F%E7%9A%84|title=\u6551\u5f7c\u547d\uff0c\u6551\u5df1\u5fc3\u2014\u2014\u653e\u751f\u7684\u91cd\u8981\u6027}}</ref>\n#Making great vows: When one makes a vow, he or she will be motivated to fulfill the vow. The vow then becomes very strong energy; it can overcome countless obstacles. This is especially true when one makes a vow out of compassion. Seeing the suffering and hearing the cries of sentient beings, Bodhisattvas bring forth immense compassion and vow to benefit all sentient beings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dharmawheel.net/viewtopic.php?t=19411|title=Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door - Dharma Wheel|website=dharmawheel.net}}</ref>\n\n===Organization===\nOn Jun Hong Lu's official Chinese-language blog,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lujunhong2or.com/|title=\u4e1c\u65b9\u53f0\u5362\u519b\u5b8f\u53f0\u957f\u7684\u535a\u5ba2}}</ref> he emphasises the importance of Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door followers' abiding by the rules and regulations in their respective countries and regions when practicing Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lujunhong2or.com/%E4%B8%AD%E5%8D%8E%E6%96%87%E5%8C%96%E6%99%AE%E5%88%A9%E4%BC%97%E7%94%9F%E6%8C%87%E5%AF%BC%E4%BA%BA%E7%94%9F-%E4%BD%9B%E6%B3%95%E7%B2%BE%E9%AB%93%E6%95%91%E5%BA%A6%E4%BC%97%E7%94%9F%E8%A7%89%E6%82%9F/|title=\u4e2d\u534e\u6587\u5316\u666e\u5229\u4f17\u751f\u6307\u5bfc\u4eba\u751f \u4f5b\u6cd5\u7cbe\u9ad3\u6551\u5ea6\u4f17\u751f\u89c9\u609f\u4eba\u751f \u2014\u20142016\u5e74\u9999\u6e2f\u5362\u519b\u5b8f\u53f0\u957f\u4e16\u754c\u5927\u578b\u5f18\u6cd5\u6d3b\u52a8\u76db\u5927\u5f00\u5e55 : \u4e1c\u65b9\u53f0\u5362\u519b\u5b8f\u53f0\u957f\u7684\u535a\u5ba2}}</ref>\n\n===Religions===\nIn an interview with [[Radio France internationale]], Lu stated that \"The reason of having 84,000 Dharma is to accommodate all beings and creatures to understand One's self in order to create a soulful world. It will be good enough as long as you have the heart and soul to create a better place for all beings. That is why I respect the Dharma. It doesn't matter which Dharma you choose; it will still be the path that you have to proceed. This is a very important point. Therefore, Chinese in Sydney will practice vegetarian during the first and the fifteenth of the Chinese calendar. There are also a lot of Chinese worshipping the Buddha during festive seasons. Some even know how to practice loving kindness. A few organizations in Sydney such as the [[Tzu Chi Foundation]], [[Pure Land Buddhism]] by Master [[Chin Kung]] and also Master [[Hsing Yun]]'s [[Nan Tien temple]] are all well established with the same priority, and that is to carry forward the Buddhism Teaching in order to unite everyone physically, mentally and soulfully. Hence, I believe that every Buddhist Chinese from all over the world should continue to practice Buddhism as it will benefit in the cultivation of One's mindset, and also to create a peaceful and harmonious world.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rfi.fr/cn/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD/20120718-%E8%87%AA%E5%BA%A6%E5%BA%A6%E4%BA%BA-%E9%87%87%E8%AE%BF%E6%BE%B3%E6%B4%B2%E5%8D%8E%E4%BA%BA%E4%BD%9B%E6%95%99%E5%AD%A6%E4%BC%9A%E5%8D%A2%E5%86%9B%E5%AE%8F%E4%BC%9A%E9%95%BF|title=\u4e2d\u534e\u4e16\u754c - \u81ea\u5ea6\u6e21\u4eba-\u91c7\u8bbf\u6fb3\u6d32\u534e\u4eba\u4f5b\u6559\u5b66\u4f1a\u5362\u519b\u5b8f\u4f1a\u957f|date=18 July 2012|website=RFI - \u6cd5\u56fd\u56fd\u9645\u5e7f\u64ad\u7535\u53f0}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 2014, Jun Hong Lu established the Australia Oriental Media Buddhist Charity Association (AOMB). AOMB reaches out to people suffering from mental illnesses, raises money for adults and children with disabilities and organises charitable events to support disaster relief efforts around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aombca.org/%E6%9C%BA%E6%9E%84%E7%AE%80%E4%BB%8B|title=\u6fb3\u6d32\u4e1c\u65b9\u4f20\u5a92\u79ef\u5584\u673a\u6784}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nThe Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door created by Lu Jun Hong had claim itself that it is part of Buddhism. However, it is criticized by the public and other religious organization that Lu's teaching are unrelated to [[Buddhism]]. One of the example pointed out by the religious specialist which is the Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door teaches the believer to burn the yellow paper, known as \"Little house\". It was pointed out that there is no such teaching in [[Buddhism]] and therefore it is unrelated. Sales of these \"Little House\" along with donations has allegedly illegally gained millions of yuan per year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.facts.org.cn/Recommendations/201711/13/t20171113_5829162.htm}}</ref>\n\nLu had several awards and speeches listed on his personal website that have no evidence or unreliable sources to support his claims. These included: a talk at [[Harvard University]] in September 2012, awards from the UK-based Unity of Faiths Foundation, the prize of \"Ambassador of World Peace\" from the UN, keynote speaker in the US Congress on March 26, 2014 along with several donations to disaster relief efforts.\n\nLu Jun Hong is criticized for making use of the religious belief for making himself famous and encourage believers to worship him. By printing his photo and name, as well as phrases to praise Lu Jun Hong on the flyer to conduct a mass advertising campaign.\n\nLu are also criticized for forcing the believers to donate money to fund his activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.itisalllie.com/|title=World Zhengxin Buddhist Association|website=en.itisalllie.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nLu's teachings have also encouraged sick believers to read scripture rather than receive medical attention. This includes believers with cancer, AIDS, infertility and mental illness.\n\n=== Malaysia Buddhism organization's reaction ===\nOn 28 December 2018, 9 Buddhism organizations from [[Malaysia]] declared that Lu Jun Hong's Guan Yin Citta belief does not match Buddhism's teaching, and urged the public to avoid attending Lu's Guan Yin Citta religious event. The 9 organizations are Malaysian Buddhist Association, Young Buddhist Association Of Malaysia / YBAM ATC, Buddhist Missionary Society Malaysia, Buddhist Maha Vihara Malaysia, Theravada Buddhist Council of Malaysia, Vajrayana Buddhist Council of Malaysia, BLIA, and Malaysian Buddhist Kulapati Association. Lu Jun Hong claim that he is able to conduct Totem reading to see a person's previous life and the doings, and as well as communicate with the Buddhist god, the [[Guanyin|GuanYin]]. The Buddhism organizations pointed out that Totem reading, using and burning the \"Little house\" does not exist in Buddhism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kwongwah.com.my/20181228/9%e5%a4%a7%e4%bd%9b%e6%95%99%e5%9b%a2%e4%bd%93%e8%81%94%e5%90%88%e5%a3%b0%e6%98%8e-%e5%90%81%e6%b0%91%e4%bc%97%e5%8b%bf%e5%87%ba%e5%b8%ad%e5%8d%a2%e5%8f%b0%e9%95%bf%e8%a7%81%e9%9d%a2%e4%bc%9a/|title=\u4e5d\u5927\u4f5b\u6559\u56e2\u4f53\u8054\u5408\u58f0\u660e \u5401\u6c11\u4f17\u52ff\u51fa\u5e2d\u5362\u53f0\u957f\u89c1\u9762\u4f1a|website=\u5149\u534e\u7f51|language=en-US|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/29/visit-of-aussie-based-buddhist-master-draws-controversy/}}</ref> They also said that their actions of promoting a [[cult of personality]] for Lu Jun Hong is not part of the Buddhist practice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/29/visit-of-aussie-based-buddhist-master-draws-controversy/|title=Visit of Aussie-based 'Buddhist Master' draws controversy {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n=== Singapore Buddhist Federation's reaction ===\nThe Singapore Buddhist Federation from [[Singapore|Republic of Singapore]] had received numerous complaints from the former believers of Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door since Lu jun Hong starts his activity, including the spreading of his Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door, advertisement campaign and set up office in [[Singapore|Republic of Singapore]]. In response, Singapore Buddhist Federation issued an statement on newspaper from Singapore, declaring the Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door is not Buddhism. As well as stating its position clearly in front of the news media by issuing the statement: \"The 'Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door' founded by [[Jun Hong Lu|Lu Jun Hong]] is attached to the Buddha's external road, not Buddhism. I hope that the believers who have joined will quickly withdraw from the 'Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door', and those who have not joined should please stay away.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.itisalllie.com/|title=World Zhengxin Buddhist Association|website=en.itisalllie.com|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Death of Liang Ping ===\nLiang Ping a 43-year-old Chinese man fell down suddenly and died in August 2015 carrying a book with Lu's teachings. A post mortem indicates death from overwork. It was later revealed that Liang woke up every day at 4 a.m. for 5 years to distribute books containing the teaching of Lu after encouragement from the organization.<ref> {{Cite web | url=https://en.australia51.com/read/8838FE98-28A1-7F1F-4C42-DD931217FB1F/}} </ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Guan Yin]]\n* [[Buddhism]]\n* [[Chinese Buddhism]]\n* [[Mahayana]]\n* [[Heart Sutra]]\n* [[N\u012blaka\u1e47\u1e6dha Dh\u0101ra\u1e47\u012b]]\n* [[World peace]]\n\n== References ==\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.facts.org.cn/Recommendations/201711/13/t20171113_5829162.htm|title=Truth on Falun Gong &#124; The Beijing News: Guan Yin Citta is an illegal organization with the cult characteristics|website=www.facts.org.cn}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/29/visit-of-aussie-based-buddhist-master-draws-controversy/|title=Visit of Aussie-based 'Buddhist Master' draws controversy &#124; The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://guanyincitta.com/en/master-lu/|title=About Master Jun Hong Lu - Guan Yin Citta}}</ref>\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|Jun hong lu}}\n* [http://guanyincitta.com/en/master-lu-biography/ Guan Yin Citta: Biography of Master Lu]\n* [http://richardjunhonglu.org Official Website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lu, Jun Hong}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Writers from Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Chinese spiritual writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chinese-Australian religious leader}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=April 2017}}\n{{COI|date=July 2016}}\n{{Third-party|date=September 2019}}\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Lu (surname \u5362)|Lu]]}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jun Hong Lu\n| native_name        = \u5362\u519b\u5b8f\n| native_name_lang   = zh\n| image              = Lu Jun Hong.jpg\n| caption            = Lu Jun Hong's photo on a advertisement flyer\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=y|1959|08|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shanghai, China]]\n| nationality        = Australian\n| occupation         = {{ubl| Chairman of Australia Oriental Media Group | President of Australian Chinese Buddhist Research Center }}\n| known_for          = Founder of the Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door\n| website            = {{url|richardjunhonglu.org}}\n| module             = {{Infobox Chinese |child =yes\n| title   = Lu Junhong\n| t       = {{linktext|\u76e7|\u8ecd|\u5b8f}}\n| s       = {{linktext|\u5362|\u519b|\u5b8f}}\n| p       = L\u00fa J\u016bnh\u00f3ng\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Jun Hong Lu''' ({{zh|t=\u76e7\u8ecd\u5b8f|p=L\u00fa J\u016bnh\u00f3ng}}, born 4 August 1959) is the leader of the organization \"Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door\" along with several other religions organizations owned by himself. The Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door created by Lu has been denounced by Malaysian Buddhist Community and Singapore Buddhist Federation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chinabuddhismencyclopedia.com/en/index.php/Malaysia_Buddhist_Community_Warns_About_Lu_Jun_Hong |title=Malaysia Buddhist Community Warns About Lu Jun Hong - Chinese Buddhist Encyclopedia |website=www.chinabuddhismencyclopedia.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://en.itisalllie.com/ |title=World Zhengxin Buddhist Association |website=en.itisalllie.com |access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nLu was born on 4 August 1959, at [[Shanghai, China]]. He later migrated to Australia in the late 80s and became an Australian citizen.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://guanyincitta.com/en/master-lu-biography/ |title=Biography of Master Jun Hong Lu - Guan Yin Citta}}</ref> In 2010, he launched the Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door organization and created the Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door religious belief.\n\n== Awards ==\nOn 31 March 2014, Lu was awarded an honorary visiting professorship by the [[University of Siena]], Italy through their Master Program in Global Governance and Cultural Diplomacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guanyincitta.com/en/master-lu-awarded-honorary-visiting-professorship-by-university-of-siena-in-italy/ |title=Master Lu Awarded Honorary Visiting Professorship by University of Siena in Italy |publisher=Guan Yin Citta |accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nJun Hong Lu is featured in the 2014 edition of the \u201cYearbook of Who's Who of China 2014\".<ref>''\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u7269\u5e74\u9274 2014''. ''\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u7269\u5e74\u9274\u793e'', 2014. p451.</ref>\n\n== Religious activities ==\n[[File:Sportshub-Singapore-Jun-Hong-Lu.jpg|upright|thumb|The Grand Dharma Talk by Jun Hong Lu in National Stadium Singapore 2017]]\n[[File:Jun Hong Lu giving a conference at Paris-Bercy - 2019-09-08.jpg|thumb|Jun Hong Lu giving a conference at [[AccorHotels Arena]] at Paris in 2019 ]]\nLu create an organization in 2010 and publicizes his own religious belief called Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door (Chinese: \u89c0\u4e16\u97f3\u83e9\u85a9\u5fc3\u9748\u6cd5\u9580). Since 2010, Lu and his Propagating Team respond to Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door follower's invitations by organizing public talks in many countries and regions including major cities in Australia; New York, Los Angeles, San Francisco and Boston in the United States; and Toronto and Vancouver in Canada, Brussels in Belgium and Madrid in Spain and Rome in Italy. Lu also gave talks in Singapore, Malaysia, Hong Kong, UK, France, Germany, Denmark, Thailand, New Zealand, and Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guanyincitta.com/en/events/|title=Events|publisher=Guan Yin Citta|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> The Dharma Convention held by Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door allows visitors to enter for free. And also, the discipleship initiation ceremony is conducted for free.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/dharma-facts/|title=Guan Yin Citta Convention - Free Entrance|last=Facts|first=Dharma}}</ref> In December 2013 Lu was invited to give a speech at Institute for Cultural Diplomacy (ICD)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cd-n.org/|title=CD-N.ORG &#124;}}</ref> in recognition of Jun Hong Lu's contribution to the international community.\n\n==Publications==\nLu has written more than 30 books related to Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door, and giving away his books for free,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gyph.org/xinlingfamenshuji/|title=\u5362\u53f0\u957f \u89c2\u4e16\u97f3\u83e9\u8428 \u5fc3\u7075\u6cd5\u95e8 \u4e66\u7c4d - \u5362\u53f0\u957f\u8457}}</ref> and some of his books were being translated into English, French, Spanish and German.<ref>[http://richardjunhonglu.org/jun-hong-lu-publications/ Publications - Master Jun Hong Lu | Official Website<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Although it claims that the books are giving away for free, Lu also sell his books to his believers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.itisalllie.com/|title=World Zhengxin Buddhist Association|website=en.itisalllie.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\n=== Buddhism and Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door ===\nAccording to Jun Hong Lu, Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door belongs to the [[Mahayana]] Buddhist tradition, and he encourages people to recite Buddhist scriptures (sutras and mantras) on a daily basis, practice life liberation (that is, saving the lives of beings destined for slaughter), and make great vows to help more people. He created the three \"golden practices\" and also claim that it will lay a solid foundation for improved physical and mental well-being.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |date= |title=Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door |url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B_Rz2U4PrI50VU1xUi1JZkxSVEE/view |location= |publisher= |page=4 |isbn=}}</ref>\n\n====3 steps of Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door's practice====\n#Reciting Buddhist sutras/mantras: Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door believes that reciting Buddhist sutras and mantras on a daily basis helps one benefit from the blessings of Buddhas and Bodhisattvas. Recitation will not only help eliminate one's negative karma; it will also bring strength, wisdom and inner peace, so that one can overcome all kinds of obstacles. The three major sutras and mantras recited by Guan Yin Citta followers are: [[N\u012blaka\u1e47\u1e6dha Dh\u0101ra\u1e47\u012b|the Great Compassion Mantra]], the [[Heart Sutra]], and the Eighty-eight Buddhas Repentance.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |date= |title=Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door |url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B_Rz2U4PrI50VU1xUi1JZkxSVEE/view |location= |publisher= |page=7 |isbn=}}</ref>\n#Practicing life liberation: that is, Release of animals, especially those in grave danger of being killed, is a popular practice performed by all schools of [[Buddhism]]. Guan Yin Citta believes that setting animals free helps one cultivate compassion towards all beings, and deepens the understanding that all living beings are all interdependent.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://lujunhong2or.com/%E7%B2%BE%E5%BD%A9%E5%BC%80%E7%A4%BA%E4%B8%93%E9%A2%98%EF%BC%9A%E6%95%91%E5%BD%BC%E5%91%BD%EF%BC%8C%E6%95%91%E5%B7%B1%E5%BF%83%EF%BC%88%E4%B8%8A%EF%BC%89-%E6%94%BE%E7%94%9F%E7%9A%84|title=\u6551\u5f7c\u547d\uff0c\u6551\u5df1\u5fc3\u2014\u2014\u653e\u751f\u7684\u91cd\u8981\u6027}}</ref>\n#Making great vows: When one makes a vow, he or she will be motivated to fulfill the vow. The vow then becomes very strong energy; it can overcome countless obstacles. This is especially true when one makes a vow out of compassion. Seeing the suffering and hearing the cries of sentient beings, Bodhisattvas bring forth immense compassion and vow to benefit all sentient beings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dharmawheel.net/viewtopic.php?t=19411|title=Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door - Dharma Wheel|website=dharmawheel.net}}</ref>\n\n===Organization===\nOn Jun Hong Lu's official Chinese-language blog,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lujunhong2or.com/|title=\u4e1c\u65b9\u53f0\u5362\u519b\u5b8f\u53f0\u957f\u7684\u535a\u5ba2}}</ref> he emphasises the importance of Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door followers' abiding by the rules and regulations in their respective countries and regions when practicing Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lujunhong2or.com/%E4%B8%AD%E5%8D%8E%E6%96%87%E5%8C%96%E6%99%AE%E5%88%A9%E4%BC%97%E7%94%9F%E6%8C%87%E5%AF%BC%E4%BA%BA%E7%94%9F-%E4%BD%9B%E6%B3%95%E7%B2%BE%E9%AB%93%E6%95%91%E5%BA%A6%E4%BC%97%E7%94%9F%E8%A7%89%E6%82%9F/|title=\u4e2d\u534e\u6587\u5316\u666e\u5229\u4f17\u751f\u6307\u5bfc\u4eba\u751f \u4f5b\u6cd5\u7cbe\u9ad3\u6551\u5ea6\u4f17\u751f\u89c9\u609f\u4eba\u751f \u2014\u20142016\u5e74\u9999\u6e2f\u5362\u519b\u5b8f\u53f0\u957f\u4e16\u754c\u5927\u578b\u5f18\u6cd5\u6d3b\u52a8\u76db\u5927\u5f00\u5e55 : \u4e1c\u65b9\u53f0\u5362\u519b\u5b8f\u53f0\u957f\u7684\u535a\u5ba2}}</ref>\n\n===Religions===\nIn an interview with [[Radio France internationale]], Lu stated that \"The reason of having 84,000 Dharma is to accommodate all beings and creatures to understand One's self in order to create a soulful world. It will be good enough as long as you have the heart and soul to create a better place for all beings. That is why I respect the Dharma. It doesn't matter which Dharma you choose; it will still be the path that you have to proceed. This is a very important point. Therefore, Chinese in Sydney will practice vegetarian during the first and the fifteenth of the Chinese calendar. There are also a lot of Chinese worshipping the Buddha during festive seasons. Some even know how to practice loving kindness. A few organizations in Sydney such as the [[Tzu Chi Foundation]], [[Pure Land Buddhism]] by Master [[Chin Kung]] and also Master [[Hsing Yun]]'s [[Nan Tien temple]] are all well established with the same priority, and that is to carry forward the Buddhism Teaching in order to unite everyone physically, mentally and soulfully. Hence, I believe that every Buddhist Chinese from all over the world should continue to practice Buddhism as it will benefit in the cultivation of One's mindset, and also to create a peaceful and harmonious world.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rfi.fr/cn/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD/20120718-%E8%87%AA%E5%BA%A6%E5%BA%A6%E4%BA%BA-%E9%87%87%E8%AE%BF%E6%BE%B3%E6%B4%B2%E5%8D%8E%E4%BA%BA%E4%BD%9B%E6%95%99%E5%AD%A6%E4%BC%9A%E5%8D%A2%E5%86%9B%E5%AE%8F%E4%BC%9A%E9%95%BF|title=\u4e2d\u534e\u4e16\u754c - \u81ea\u5ea6\u6e21\u4eba-\u91c7\u8bbf\u6fb3\u6d32\u534e\u4eba\u4f5b\u6559\u5b66\u4f1a\u5362\u519b\u5b8f\u4f1a\u957f|date=18 July 2012|website=RFI - \u6cd5\u56fd\u56fd\u9645\u5e7f\u64ad\u7535\u53f0}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 2014, Jun Hong Lu established the Australia Oriental Media Buddhist Charity Association (AOMB). AOMB reaches out to people suffering from mental illnesses, raises money for adults and children with disabilities and organises charitable events to support disaster relief efforts around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aombca.org/%E6%9C%BA%E6%9E%84%E7%AE%80%E4%BB%8B|title=\u6fb3\u6d32\u4e1c\u65b9\u4f20\u5a92\u79ef\u5584\u673a\u6784}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nThe Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door created by Lu Jun Hong had claim itself that it is part of Buddhism. However, it is criticized by the public and other religious organization that Lu's teaching are unrelated to [[Buddhism]]. One of the example pointed out by the religious specialist which is the Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door teaches the believer to burn the yellow paper, known as \"Little house\". It was pointed out that there is no such teaching in [[Buddhism]] and therefore it is unrelated. Sales of these \"Little House\" along with donations has allegiedly illegally gains millions of yuan per year<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.facts.org.cn/Recommendations/201711/13/t20171113_5829162.htm}}.</ref>\n\nLu had several awards and speeches listed on his personal website that have no evidence or unreliable sources to support his claims. These included: a talk at [[Harvard University]] in September 2012, awards from the UK-based Unity of Faiths Foundation, the prize of \"Ambassador of World Peace\" from the UN, keynote speaker in the US Congress in March 26, 2014 along with several donations to disaster relief efforts.\n\nLu Jun Hong are criticized for making use the religious belief for making himself famous and encourage believers to worship him. By printing his photo and name, as well as phrases to praise Lu Jun Hong on the flyer to conduct mass advertising campaign.\n\nLu are also criticized for forcing the believers to donate money to fund his activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.itisalllie.com/|title=World Zhengxin Buddhist Association|website=en.itisalllie.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nLu's teaching have also encouraged sick believers to read scripture rather than receive medical attention. This includes believers with cancer, AIDS, infertility and mental illness.\n\n=== Malaysia Buddhism organization's reaction ===\nOn 28 December 2018, 9 Buddhism organizations from [[Malaysia]] declared that Lu Jun Hong's Guan Yin Citta belief does not matches the Buddhism's teaching, and urged the public to avoid attending Lu's Guan Yin Citta religious event. The 9 organizations are Malaysian Buddhist Association, Young Buddhist Association Of Malaysia / YBAM ATC, Buddhist Missionary Society Malaysia, Buddhist Maha Vihara Malaysia,Theravada Buddhist Council of Malaysia, Vajrayana Buddhist Council of Malaysia, BLIA, and Malaysian Buddhist Kulapati Association. Lu Jun Hong claim that he is able to conduct Totem reading to see a person's previous life and the doings, and as well as communicate with the Buddhist god, the [[Guanyin|GuanYin]]. The Buddhism organizations pointed out that Totem reading, using and burning the \"Little house\" does not exist in Buddhism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kwongwah.com.my/20181228/9%e5%a4%a7%e4%bd%9b%e6%95%99%e5%9b%a2%e4%bd%93%e8%81%94%e5%90%88%e5%a3%b0%e6%98%8e-%e5%90%81%e6%b0%91%e4%bc%97%e5%8b%bf%e5%87%ba%e5%b8%ad%e5%8d%a2%e5%8f%b0%e9%95%bf%e8%a7%81%e9%9d%a2%e4%bc%9a/|title=\u4e5d\u5927\u4f5b\u6559\u56e2\u4f53\u8054\u5408\u58f0\u660e \u5401\u6c11\u4f17\u52ff\u51fa\u5e2d\u5362\u53f0\u957f\u89c1\u9762\u4f1a|website=\u5149\u534e\u7f51|language=en-US|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/29/visit-of-aussie-based-buddhist-master-draws-controversy/}}</ref> They also said that their actions of promoting a [[cult of personality]] for Lu Jun Hong is not part of the Buddhist practice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/29/visit-of-aussie-based-buddhist-master-draws-controversy/|title=Visit of Aussie-based 'Buddhist Master' draws controversy {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n=== Singapore Buddhist Federation's reaction ===\nThe Singapore Buddhist Federation from [[Singapore|Republic of Singapore]] had received numerous complaints from the former believers of Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door since Lu jun Hong starts his activity, including the spreading of his Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door, advertisement campaign and set up office in [[Singapore|Republic of Singapore]]. In response, Singapore Buddhist Federation issued an statement on newspaper from Singapore, declaring the Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door is not Buddhism. As well as stating it's position clearly in front of the news media by issuing the statement: \"The 'Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door' founded by [[Jun Hong Lu|Lu Jun Hong]] is attached to the Buddha's external road, not Buddhism. I hope that the believers who have joined will quickly withdraw from the 'Guan Yin Citta Dharma Door', and those who have not joined should please stay away.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.itisalllie.com/|title=World Zhengxin Buddhist Association|website=en.itisalllie.com|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Death of Liang Ping ===\nLiang Ping a 43 year old Chinese man fell down suddenly and died in August 2015 carrying a book with Lu's teachings. A post morturm indicates death from overwork. It was later revealed that Liang woke up every day at 4 a.m. for 5 years to distribute books containing the teaching of Lu after encouragement from the organization.<ref> {{Cite web | url=https://en.australia51.com/read/8838FE98-28A1-7F1F-4C42-DD931217FB1F/}} </ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Guan Yin]]\n* [[Buddhism]]\n* [[Chinese Buddhism]]\n* [[Mahayana]]\n* [[Heart Sutra]]\n* [[N\u012blaka\u1e47\u1e6dha Dh\u0101ra\u1e47\u012b]]\n* [[World peace]]\n\n== References ==\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.facts.org.cn/Recommendations/201711/13/t20171113_5829162.htm|title=Truth on Falun Gong &#124; The Beijing News: Guan Yin Citta is an illegal organization with the cult characteristics|website=www.facts.org.cn}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/29/visit-of-aussie-based-buddhist-master-draws-controversy/|title=Visit of Aussie-based 'Buddhist Master' draws controversy &#124; The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://guanyincitta.com/en/master-lu/|title=About Master Jun Hong Lu - Guan Yin Citta}}</ref>\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|Jun hong lu}}\n* [http://guanyincitta.com/en/master-lu-biography/ Guan Yin Citta: Biography of Master Lu]\n* [http://richardjunhonglu.org Official Website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lu, Jun Hong}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Writers from Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Chinese spiritual writers]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "it's \u2192 its; copy edit", "url_page": "//